# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: graphics
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:graphics/color-space] A **color space** is a specific organization of colors.
[src:graphics/color-space] In combination with color profiling supported by various physical devices, it supports reproducible representations of color – whether such representation entails an analog or a digital representation.
[src:graphics/color-space] A "color space" is a useful conceptual tool for understanding the color capabilities of a particular device or digital file.
[src:graphics/color-space] When trying to reproduce color on another device, color spaces can show whether shadow/highlight detail and color saturation can be retained, and by how much either will be compromised.
[src:graphics/color-space] Adding a specific mapping function between a color model and a reference color space establishes within the reference color space a definite "footprint", known as a *gamut*, and for a given color model, this defines a color space.
[src:graphics/color-space] For example, Adobe RGB and sRGB are two different absolute color spaces, both based on the RGB color model.
[src:graphics/color-space] When defining a color space, the usual reference standard is the CIELAB or CIEXYZ color spaces, which were specifically designed to encompass all colors the average human can see.
[src:graphics/color-space] Since "color space" identifies a particular combination of the color model and the mapping function, the word is often used informally to identify a color model.
[src:graphics/color-space] However, even though identifying a color space automatically identifies the associated color model, this usage is incorrect in a strict sense.
[src:graphics/color-space] For example, although several specific color spaces are based on the RGB color model, there is no such thing as the singular RGB color space.
[src:graphics/color-space] In 1802, Thomas Young postulated the existence of three types of photoreceptors (now known as cone cells) in the eye, each of which was sensitive to a particular range of visible light.
[src:graphics/color-space] Hermann von Helmholtz developed the Young–Helmholtz theory further in 1850: that the three types of cone photoreceptors could be classified as short-preferring (blue), middle-preferring (green), and long-preferring (red), according to their response to the wavelengths of light striking the retina.
[src:graphics/color-space] The relative strengths of the signals detected by the three types of cones are interpreted by the brain as a visible color.
[src:graphics/color-space] But it is not clear that they thought of colors as being points in color space.
[src:graphics/color-space] The color-space concept was likely due to Hermann Grassmann, who developed it in two stages.
[src:graphics/color-space] First, he developed the idea of vector space, which allowed the algebraic representation of geometric concepts in *n*-dimensional space.
[src:graphics/color-space] With this conceptual background, in 1853, Grassmann published a theory of how colors mix; it and its three color laws are still taught, as Grassmann's law.
[src:graphics/color-space] Colors can be created in printing with color spaces based on the CMYK color model, using the subtractive primary colors of pigment (**c**yan, **m**agenta, **y**ellow, and **k**ey [black]).
[src:graphics/color-space] To create a three-dimensional representation of a given color space, we can assign the amount of magenta color to the representation's X axis, the amount of cyan to its Y axis, and the amount of yellow to its Z axis.
[src:graphics/color-space] The resulting 3-D space provides a unique position for every possible color that can be created by combining those three pigments.
[src:graphics/color-space] Colors can be created on computer monitors with color spaces based on the RGB color model, using the additive primary colors (red, green, and blue).
[src:graphics/color-space] A three-dimensional representation would assign each of the three colors to the X, Y, and Z axes.
[src:graphics/color-space] Colors generated on a given monitor will be limited by the reproduction medium, such as the phosphor (in a CRT monitor) or filters and backlight (LCD monitor).
[src:graphics/color-space] Another way of creating colors on a monitor is with an HSL or HSV color model, based on hue, saturation, brightness (value/lightness).
[src:graphics/color-space] With such a model, the variables are assigned to cylindrical coordinates.
[src:graphics/color-space] Many color spaces can be represented as three-dimensional values in this manner, but some have more, or fewer dimensions, and some, such as Pantone, cannot be represented in this way at all.
[src:graphics/color-space] Color space conversion is the translation of the representation of a color from one basis to another.
[src:graphics/color-space] This typically occurs in the context of converting an image that is represented in one color space to another color space, the goal being to make the translated image look as similar as possible to the original.
[src:graphics/color-space] The RGB color model is implemented in different ways, depending on the capabilities of the system used.
[src:graphics/color-space] The most common incarnation in general use as of 2021 is the 24-bit implementation, with 8 bits, or 256 discrete levels of color per channel.
[src:graphics/color-space] Any color space based on such a 24-bit RGB model is thus limited to a range of 256×256×256 ≈ 16.7 million colors.
[src:graphics/color-space] Some implementations use 16 bits per component for 48 bits total, resulting in the same gamut with a larger number of distinct colors.
[src:graphics/color-space] This is especially important when working with wide-gamut color spaces (where most of the more common colors are located relatively close together), or when a large number of digital filtering algorithms are used consecutively.
[src:graphics/color-space] The same principle applies for any color space based on the same color model, but implemented at different bit depths.
[src:graphics/color-space] CIE 1931 XYZ color space was one of the first attempts to produce a color space based on measurements of human color perception (earlier efforts were by James Clerk Maxwell, König & Dieterici, and Abney at Imperial College) and it is the basis for almost all other color spaces.
[src:graphics/color-space] The CIERGB color space is a linearly-related companion of CIE XYZ.
[src:graphics/color-space] Additional derivatives of CIE XYZ include the CIELUV, CIEUVW, and CIELAB.
[src:graphics/color-space] RGB uses additive color mixing, because it describes what kind of *light* needs to be *emitted* to produce a given color.
[src:graphics/color-space] RGB stores individual values for red, green and blue.
[src:graphics/color-space] RGBA is RGB with an additional channel, alpha, to indicate transparency.
[src:graphics/color-space] Common color spaces based on the RGB model include sRGB, Adobe RGB, ProPhoto RGB, scRGB, and CIE RGB.
[src:graphics/color-space] CMYK uses subtractive color mixing used in the printing process, because it describes what kind of inks need to be applied so the light *reflected* from the substrate and through the inks produces a given color.
[src:graphics/color-space] One starts with a white substrate (canvas, page, etc.), and uses ink to subtract color from white to create an image.
[src:graphics/color-space] CMYK stores ink values for cyan, magenta, yellow and black.
[src:graphics/color-space] There are many CMYK color spaces for different sets of inks, substrates, and press characteristics (which change the dot gain or transfer function for each ink and thus change the appearance).
[src:graphics/color-space] YIQ was formerly used in NTSC (North America, Japan and elsewhere) television broadcasts for historical reasons.
[src:graphics/color-space] This system stores a luma value roughly analogous to (and sometimes incorrectly identified as) luminance, along with two chroma values as approximate representations of the relative amounts of blue and red in the color.
[src:graphics/color-space] It is similar to the YUV scheme used in most video capture systems and in PAL (Australia, Europe, except France, which uses SECAM) television, except that the YIQ color space is rotated 33° with respect to the YUV color space and the color axes are swapped.
[src:graphics/color-space] The YDbDr scheme used by SECAM television is rotated in another way.
[src:graphics/color-space] It is most commonly seen in its digital form, YCbCr, used widely in video and image compression schemes such as MPEG and JPEG.
[src:graphics/color-space] xvYCC is an international digital video color space standard published by the IEC (IEC 61966-2-4).
[src:graphics/color-space] It is based on the ITU BT.601 and BT.709 standards but extends the gamut beyond the R/G/B primaries specified in those standards.
[src:graphics/color-space] HSV (**h**ue, **s**aturation, **v**alue), also known as HSB (hue, saturation, **b**rightness) is often used by artists because it is often more natural to think about a color in terms of hue and saturation than in terms of additive or subtractive color components.
[src:graphics/color-space] HSV is a transformation of an RGB color space, and its components and colorimetry are relative to the RGB color space from which it was derived.
[src:graphics/color-space] HSL (**h**ue, **s**aturation, **l**ightness/**l**uminance), also known as HLS or HSI (hue, saturation, **i**ntensity) is quite similar to HSV, with "lightness" replacing "brightness".
[src:graphics/color-space] The difference is that the *brightness* of a pure color is equal to the brightness of white, while the *lightness* of a pure color is equal to the lightness of a medium gray.
[src:graphics/color-space] They largely ignored blue light because the added complexity of a 3-component process provided only a marginal increase in fidelity when compared to the jump from monochrome to 2-component color.
[src:graphics/color-space] In this article, we concentrate on the second definition.
[src:graphics/color-space] CIEXYZ, sRGB, and ICtCp are examples of absolute color spaces, as opposed to a generic RGB color space.
[src:graphics/color-space] A non-absolute color space can be made absolute by defining its relationship to absolute colorimetric quantities.
[src:graphics/color-space] For instance, if the red, green, and blue colors in a monitor are measured exactly, together with other properties of the monitor, then RGB values on that monitor can be considered as absolute.
[src:graphics/color-space] The CIE 1976 L*, a*, b* color space is sometimes referred to as absolute, though it also needs a white point specification to make it so.
[src:graphics/color-space] A popular way to make a color space like RGB into an absolute color is to define an ICC profile, which contains the attributes of the RGB.
[src:graphics/color-space] This is not the only way to express an absolute color, but it is the standard in many industries.
[src:graphics/color-space] RGB colors defined by widely accepted profiles include sRGB and Adobe RGB.
[src:graphics/color-space] The process of adding an ICC profile to a graphic or document is sometimes called *tagging* or *embedding*; tagging, therefore, marks the absolute meaning of colors in that graphic or document.
[src:graphics/color-space] A color in one absolute color space can be converted into another absolute color space, and back again, in general; however, some color spaces may have gamut limitations, and converting colors that lie outside that gamut will not produce correct results.
[src:graphics/color-space] There are also likely to be rounding errors, especially if the popular range of only 256 distinct values per component (8-bit color) is used.
[src:graphics/color-space] One part of the definition of an absolute color space is the viewing conditions.
[src:graphics/color-space] The same color, viewed under different natural or artificial lighting conditions, will look different.
[src:graphics/color-space] Those involved professionally with color matching may use viewing rooms, lit by standardized lighting.
[src:graphics/color-space] Occasionally, there are precise rules for converting between non-absolute color spaces.
[src:graphics/color-space] For example, HSL and HSV spaces are defined as mappings of RGB.
[src:graphics/color-space] Both are non-absolute, but the conversion between them should maintain the same color.
[src:graphics/color-space] However, in general, converting between two non-absolute color spaces (for example, RGB to CMYK) or between absolute and non-absolute color spaces (for example, RGB to L*a*b*) is almost a meaningless concept.
[src:graphics/color-space] A different method of defining absolute color spaces is familiar to many consumers as the swatch card, used to select paint, fabrics, and the like.
[src:graphics/color-space] This is a way of agreeing a color between two parties.
[src:graphics/color-space] A more standardized method of defining absolute colors is the Pantone Matching System, a proprietary system that includes swatch cards and recipes that commercial printers can use to make inks that are a particular color.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] Computer graphics is responsible for displaying art and image data effectively and meaningfully to the consumer.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] It is also used for processing image data received from the physical world, such as photo and video content.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] Computer graphics development has had a significant impact on many types of media and has revolutionized animation, movies, advertising, and video games in general.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] The term computer graphics has been used in a broad sense to describe "almost everything on computers that is not text or sound".
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] Such imagery is found in and on television, newspapers, weather reports, and in a variety of medical investigations and surgical procedures.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] A well-constructed graph can present complex statistics in a form that is easier to understand and interpret.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] In the media "such graphs are used to illustrate papers, reports, theses", and other presentation material.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] Many tools have been developed to visualize data.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] Computer-generated imagery can be categorized into several different types: two dimensional (2D), three dimensional (3D), and animated graphics.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] As technology has improved, 3D computer graphics have become more common, but 2D computer graphics are still widely used.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] Computer graphics has emerged as a sub-field of computer science which studies methods for digitally synthesizing and manipulating visual content.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] The precursor sciences to the development of modern computer graphics were the advances in electrical engineering, electronics, and television that took place during the first half of the twentieth century.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] Screens could display art since the Lumiere brothers' use of mattes to create special effects for the earliest films dating from 1895, but such displays were limited and not interactive.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] The first cathode ray tube, the Braun tube, was invented in 1897 – it in turn would permit the oscilloscope and the military control panel – the more direct precursors of the field, as they provided the first two-dimensional electronic displays that responded to programmatic or user input.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] New kinds of displays were needed to process the wealth of information resulting from such projects, leading to the development of computer graphics as a discipline.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] Early projects like the Whirlwind and SAGE Projects introduced the CRT as a viable display and interaction interface and introduced the light pen as an input device.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] Ross of the Whirlwind SAGE system performed a personal experiment in which he wrote a small program that captured the movement of his finger and displayed its vector (his traced name) on a display scope.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] One of the first interactive video games to feature recognizable, interactive graphics – *Tennis for Two* – was created for an oscilloscope by William Higinbotham to entertain visitors in 1958 at Brookhaven National Laboratory and simulated a tennis match.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] Ross, while working at MIT on transforming mathematic statements into computer generated 3D machine tool vectors, created a display scope image of a Disney cartoon character.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] Electronics pioneer Hewlett-Packard went public in 1957 after incorporating the decade prior, and established strong ties with Stanford University through its founders, who were alumni.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] This began the decades-long transformation of the southern San Francisco Bay Area into the world's leading computer technology hub – now known as Silicon Valley.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] The field of computer graphics developed with the emergence of computer graphics hardware.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] Further advances in computing led to greater advancements in interactive computer graphics.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] In 1959, the TX-2 computer was developed at MIT's Lincoln Laboratory.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] The TX-2 integrated a number of new man-machine interfaces.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] A light pen could be used to draw sketches on the computer using Ivan Sutherland's revolutionary Sketchpad software.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] Using a light pen, Sketchpad allowed one to draw simple shapes on the computer screen, save them and even recall them later.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] The light pen itself had a small photoelectric cell in its tip.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] This cell emitted an electronic pulse whenever it was placed in front of a computer screen and the screen's electron gun fired directly at it.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] By simply timing the electronic pulse with the current location of the electron gun, it was easy to pinpoint exactly where the pen was on the screen at any given moment.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] Once that was determined, the computer could then draw a cursor at that location.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] Sutherland seemed to find the perfect solution for many of the graphics problems he faced.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] Even today, many standards of computer graphics interfaces got their start with this early Sketchpad program.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] One example of this is in drawing constraints.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] If one wants to draw a square for example, they do not have to worry about drawing four lines perfectly to form the edges of the box.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] One can simply specify that they want to draw a box, and then specify the location and size of the box.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] The software will then construct a perfect box, with the right dimensions and at the right location.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] Another example is that Sutherland's software modeled objects – not just a picture of objects.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] In other words, with a model of a car, one could change the size of the tires without affecting the rest of the car.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] It could stretch the body of car without deforming the tires.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] The phrase "computer graphics" has been credited to William Fetter, a graphic designer for Boeing in 1960.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] Fetter in turn attributed it to Verne Hudson, also at Boeing.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] In 1961 another student at MIT, Steve Russell, created another important title in the history of video games, *Spacewar!* Written for the DEC PDP-1, *Spacewar* was an instant success and copies started flowing to other PDP-1 owners and eventually DEC got a copy.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] The engineers at DEC used it as a diagnostic program on every new PDP-1 before shipping it.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] The sales force picked up on this quickly enough and when installing new units, would run the "world's first video game" for their new customers.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] At around the same time (1961–1962) in the University of Cambridge, Elizabeth Waldram wrote code to display radio-astronomy maps on a cathode ray tube.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] Zajac, a scientist at Bell Telephone Laboratory (BTL), created a film called "Simulation of a two-giro gravity attitude control system" in 1963.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] In this computer-generated film, Zajac showed how the attitude of a satellite could be altered as it orbits the Earth.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] He created the animation on an IBM 7090 mainframe computer.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] Also at BTL, Ken Knowlton, Frank Sinden, Ruth A.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] Weiss and Michael Noll started working in the computer graphics field.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] Sinden created a film called *Force, Mass and Motion* illustrating Newton's laws of motion in operation.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] Around the same time, other scientists were creating computer graphics to illustrate their research.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] At Lawrence Radiation Laboratory, Nelson Max created the films *Flow of a Viscous Fluid* and *Propagation of Shock Waves in a Solid Form*.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] Boeing Aircraft created a film called *Vibration of an Aircraft*.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] Also sometime in the early 1960s, automobiles would also provide a boost through the early work of Pierre Bézier at Renault, who used Paul de Casteljau's curves – now called Bézier curves after Bézier's work in the field – to develop 3d modeling techniques for Renault car bodies.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] These curves would form the foundation for much curve-modeling work in the field, as curves – unlike polygons – are mathematically complex entities to draw and model well.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] It was not long before major corporations started taking an interest in computer graphics.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] TRW, Lockheed-Georgia, General Electric and Sperry Rand are among the many companies that were getting started in computer graphics by the mid-1960s.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] IBM was quick to respond to this interest by releasing the IBM 2250 graphics terminal, the first commercially available graphics computer.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] Ralph Baer, a supervising engineer at Sanders Associates, came up with a home video game in 1966 that was later licensed to Magnavox and called the Odyssey.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] While very simplistic, and requiring fairly inexpensive electronic parts, it allowed the player to move points of light around on a screen.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] It was the first consumer computer graphics product.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] Evans was director of engineering at Bendix Corporation's computer division from 1953 to 1962, after which he worked for the next five years as a visiting professor at Berkeley.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] There he continued his interest in computers and how they interfaced with people.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] In 1966, the University of Utah recruited Evans to form a computer science program, and computer graphics quickly became his primary interest.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] This new department would become the world's primary research center for computer graphics through the 1970s.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] Also, in 1966, Ivan Sutherland continued to innovate at MIT when he invented the first computer-controlled head-mounted display (HMD).
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] It displayed two separate wireframe images, one for each eye.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] This allowed the viewer to see the computer scene in stereoscopic 3D.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] The heavy hardware required for supporting the display and tracker was called the Sword of Damocles because of the potential danger if it were to fall upon the wearer.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] After receiving his Ph.D. from MIT, Sutherland became Director of Information Processing at ARPA (Advanced Research Projects Agency), and later became a professor at Harvard.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] There Sutherland perfected his HMD; twenty years later, NASA would re-discover his techniques in their virtual reality research.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] At Utah, Sutherland and Evans were highly sought after consultants by large companies, but they were frustrated at the lack of graphics hardware available at the time, so they started formulating a plan to start their own company.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] In 1968, Dave Evans and Ivan Sutherland founded the first computer graphics hardware company, Evans & Sutherland.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] While Sutherland originally wanted the company to be located in Cambridge, Massachusetts, Salt Lake City was instead chosen due to its proximity to the professors' research group at the University of Utah.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] In 1969, the ACM initiated A Special Interest Group on Graphics (SIGGRAPH) which organizes conferences, graphics standards, and publications within the field of computer graphics.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] By 1973, the first annual SIGGRAPH conference was held, which has become one of the focuses of the organization.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] SIGGRAPH has grown in size and importance as the field of computer graphics has expanded over time.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] Subsequently, a number of breakthroughs in the field occurred at the University of Utah in the 1970s, which had hired Ivan Sutherland.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] Evans to teach an advanced computer graphics class, which contributed a great deal of founding research to the field and taught several students who would grow to found several of the industry's most important companies – namely Pixar, Silicon Graphics, and Adobe Systems.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] Tom Stockham led the image processing group at UU which worked closely with the computer graphics lab.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] One of these students was Edwin Catmull.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] Catmull had just come from The Boeing Company and had been working on his degree in physics.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] Growing up on Disney, Catmull loved animation yet quickly discovered that he did not have the talent for drawing.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] Now Catmull (along with many others) saw computers as the natural progression of animation and they wanted to be part of the revolution.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] The first computer animation that Catmull saw was his own.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] He created an animation of his hand opening and closing.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] He also pioneered texture mapping to paint textures on three-dimensional models in 1974, now considered one of the fundamental techniques in 3D modeling.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] It became one of his goals to produce a feature-length motion picture using computer graphics – a goal he would achieve two decades later after his founding role in Pixar.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] In the same class, Fred Parke created an animation of his wife's face.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] The two animations were included in the 1976 feature film Futureworld.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] As the UU computer graphics laboratory was attracting people from all over, John Warnock was another of those early pioneers; he later founded Adobe Systems and created a revolution in the publishing world with his PostScript page description language.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] Adobe would go on later to create the industry standard photo editing software in Adobe Photoshop and a prominent movie industry special effects program in Adobe After Effects.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] James Clark was also there; he later founded Silicon Graphics, a maker of advanced rendering systems that would dominate the field of high-end graphics until the early 1990s.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] A major advance in 3D computer graphics was created at UU by these early pioneers – hidden surface determination.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] In order to draw a representation of a 3D object on the screen, the computer must determine which surfaces are "behind" the object from the viewer's perspective, and thus should be "hidden" when the computer creates (or renders) the image.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] The 3D Core Graphics System (or **Core**) was the first graphical standard to be developed.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] A group of 25 experts of the ACM Special Interest Group SIGGRAPH developed this "conceptual framework".
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] The specifications were published in 1977, and it became a foundation for many future developments in the field.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] Also in the 1970s, Henri Gouraud, Jim Blinn and Bui Tuong Phong contributed to the foundations of shading in CGI via the development of the Gouraud shading and Blinn–Phong shading models, allowing graphics to move beyond a "flat" look to a look more accurately portraying depth.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] Jim Blinn also innovated further in 1978 by introducing bump mapping, a technique for simulating uneven surfaces, and the predecessor to many more advanced kinds of mapping used today.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] The modern videogame arcade as is known today was birthed in the 1970s, with the first arcade games using real-time 2D sprite graphics.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] *Pong* in 1972 was one of the first hit arcade cabinet games.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] *Speed Race* in 1974 featured sprites moving along a vertically scrolling road.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] *Gun Fight* in 1975 featured human-looking animated characters, while *Space Invaders* in 1978 featured a large number of animated figures on screen; both used a specialized barrel shifter circuit made from discrete chips to help their Intel 8080 microprocessor animate their framebuffer graphics.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] The 1980s began to see the commercialization of computer graphics.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] As the home computer proliferated, a subject which had previously been an academics-only discipline was adopted by a much larger audience, and the number of computer graphics developers increased significantly.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] NEC's μPD7220 was the first GPU, fabricated on a fully integrated NMOS VLSI chip.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] It supported up to 1024x1024 resolution, and laid the foundations for the emerging PC graphics market.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] It was used in a number of graphics cards, and was licensed for clones such as the Intel 82720, the first of Intel's graphics processing units.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] MOS memory also became cheaper in the early 1980s, enabling the development of affordable framebuffer memory, notably video RAM (VRAM) introduced by Texas Instruments (TI) in the mid-1980s.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] In 1984, Hitachi released the ARTC HD63484, the first complementary MOS (CMOS) GPU.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] It was capable of displaying high-resolution in color mode and up to 4K resolution in monochrome mode, and it was used in a number of graphics cards and terminals during the late 1980s.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] In 1986, TI introduced the TMS34010, the first fully programmable MOS graphics processor.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] Computer graphics terminals during this decade became increasingly intelligent, semi-standalone and standalone workstations.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] Graphics and application processing were increasingly migrated to the intelligence in the workstation, rather than continuing to rely on central mainframe and minicomputers.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] The Orca 3000 was based on the 16-bit Motorola 68000 microprocessor and AMD bit-slice processors, and had Unix as its operating system.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] It was targeted squarely at the sophisticated end of the design engineering sector.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] Artists and graphic designers began to see the personal computer, particularly the Amiga and Macintosh, as a serious design tool, one that could save time and draw more accurately than other methods.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] The Macintosh remains a highly popular tool for computer graphics among graphic design studios and businesses.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] Modern computers, dating from the 1980s, often use graphical user interfaces (GUI) to present data and information with symbols, icons and pictures, rather than text.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] Graphics are one of the five key elements of multimedia technology.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] In the field of realistic rendering, Japan's Osaka University developed the LINKS-1 Computer Graphics System, a supercomputer that used up to 257 Zilog Z8001 microprocessors, in 1982, for the purpose of rendering realistic 3D computer graphics.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] According to the Information Processing Society of Japan: "The core of 3D image rendering is calculating the luminance of each pixel making up a rendered surface from the given viewpoint, light source, and object position.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] The LINKS-1 system was developed to realize an image rendering methodology in which each pixel could be parallel processed independently using ray tracing.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] By developing a new software methodology specifically for high-speed image rendering, LINKS-1 was able to rapidly render highly realistic images." The LINKS-1 was the world's most powerful computer, as of 1984.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] Also in the field of realistic rendering, the general rendering equation of David Immel and James Kajiya was developed in 1986 – an important step towards implementing global illumination, which is necessary to pursue photorealism in computer graphics.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] The continuing popularity of *Star Wars* and other science fiction franchises were relevant in cinematic CGI at this time, as Lucasfilm and Industrial Light & Magic became known as the "go-to" house by many other studios for topnotch computer graphics in film.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] Important advances in chroma keying ("bluescreening", etc.) were made for the later films of the original trilogy.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] In the late 1980s, Silicon Graphics (SGI) computers were used to create some of the first fully computer-generated short films at Pixar, and Silicon Graphics machines were considered a high-water mark for the field during the decade.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] For the arcades, advances were made in commercial, real-time 3D graphics.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] In 1988, the first dedicated real-time 3D graphics boards were introduced for arcades, with the Namco System 21 and Taito Air System.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] On the professional side, Evans & Sutherland and SGI developed 3D raster graphics hardware that directly influenced the later single-chip graphics processing unit (GPU), a technology where a separate and very powerful chip is used in parallel processing with a CPU to optimize graphics.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] The decade also saw computer graphics applied to many additional professional markets, including location-based entertainment and education with the E&S Digistar, vehicle design, vehicle simulation, and chemistry.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] The 1990s' highlight was the emergence of 3D modeling on a mass scale and an rise in the quality of CGI generally.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] By the end of the decade, the GPU would begin its rise to the prominence it still enjoys today.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] The field began to see the first rendered graphics that could truly pass as photorealistic to the untrained eye (though they could not yet do so with a trained CGI artist) and 3D graphics became far more popular in gaming, multimedia, and animation.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] In film, Pixar began its serious commercial rise in this era under Edwin Catmull, with its first major film release, in 1995 – *Toy Story* – a critical and commercial success of nine-figure magnitude.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] The studio to invent the programmable shader would go on to have many animated hits, and its work on prerendered video animation is still considered an industry leader and research trail breaker.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] In video games, in 1992, *Virtua Racing*, running on the Sega Model 1 arcade system board, laid the foundations for fully 3D racing games and popularized real-time 3D polygonal graphics among a wider audience in the video game industry.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] The Sega Model 2 in 1993 and Sega Model 3 in 1996 subsequently pushed the boundaries of commercial, real-time 3D graphics.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] Back on the PC, *Wolfenstein 3D*, *Doom* and *Quake*, three of the first massively popular 3D first-person shooter games, were released by id Software to critical and popular acclaim during this decade using a rendering engine innovated primarily by John Carmack.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] The Sony PlayStation, Sega Saturn, and Nintendo 64, among other consoles, sold in the millions and popularized 3D graphics for home gamers.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] Certain late-1990s first-generation 3D titles became seen as influential in popularizing 3D graphics among console users, such as platform games *Super Mario 64* and *The Legend of Zelda: Ocarina of Time*, and early 3D fighting games like *Virtua Fighter*, *Battle Arena Toshinden*, and *Tekken*.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] Technology and algorithms for rendering continued to improve greatly.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] In 1996, Krishnamurty and Levoy invented normal mapping – an improvement on Jim Blinn's bump mapping.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] 1999 saw Nvidia release the seminal GeForce 256, the first home video card billed as a graphics processing unit or GPU, which in its own words contained "integrated transform, lighting, triangle setup/clipping, and rendering engines".
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] By the end of the decade, computers adopted common frameworks for graphics processing such as DirectX and OpenGL.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] Since then, computer graphics have only become more detailed and realistic, due to more powerful graphics hardware and 3D modeling software.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] AMD also became a leading developer of graphics boards in this decade, creating a "duopoly" in the field which exists this day.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] CGI became ubiquitous in earnest during this era.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] Video games and CGI cinema had spread the reach of computer graphics to the mainstream by the late 1990s and continued to do so at an accelerated pace in the 2000s.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] CGI was also adopted *en masse* for television advertisements widely in the late 1990s and 2000s, and so became familiar to a massive audience.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] The continued rise and increasing sophistication of the graphics processing unit were crucial to this decade, and 3D rendering capabilities became a standard feature as 3D-graphics GPUs became considered a necessity for desktop computer makers to offer.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] The Nvidia GeForce line of graphics cards dominated the market in the early decade with occasional significant competing presence from ATI.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] As the decade progressed, even low-end machines usually contained a 3D-capable GPU of some kind as Nvidia and AMD both introduced low-priced chipsets and continued to dominate the market.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] Computer graphics used in films and video games gradually began to be realistic to the point of entering the uncanny valley.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] CGI movies proliferated, with traditional animated cartoon films like Ice Age and Madagascar as well as numerous Pixar offerings like Finding Nemo dominating the box office in this field.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] The *Final Fantasy: The Spirits Within*, released in 2001, was the first fully computer-generated feature film to use photorealistic CGI characters and be fully made with motion capture.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] The film was not a box-office success, however.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] Some commentators have suggested this may be partly because the lead CGI characters had facial features which fell into the "uncanny valley".
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] Other animated films like *The Polar Express* drew attention at this time as well.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] *Star Wars* also resurfaced with its prequel trilogy and the effects continued to set a bar for CGI in film.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] In videogames, the Sony PlayStation 2 and 3, the Microsoft Xbox line of consoles, and offerings from Nintendo such as the GameCube maintained a large following, as did the Windows PC.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] Microsoft made a decision to expose DirectX more easily to the independent developer world with the XNA program, but it was not a success.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] DirectX itself remained a commercial success, however.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] OpenGL continued to mature as well, and it and DirectX improved greatly; the second-generation shader languages HLSL and GLSL began to be popular in this decade.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] In scientific computing, the GPGPU technique to pass large amounts of data bidirectionally between a GPU and CPU was invented; speeding up analysis on many kinds of bioinformatics and molecular biology experiments.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] The technique has also been used for Bitcoin mining and has applications in computer vision.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] In the 2010s, CGI has been nearly ubiquitous in video, pre-rendered graphics are nearly scientifically photorealistic, and real-time graphics on a suitably high-end system may simulate photorealism to the untrained eye.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] Shaders are now very nearly a necessity for advanced work in the field, providing considerable complexity in manipulating pixels, vertices, and textures on a per-element basis, and countless possible effects.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] Their shader languages HLSL and GLSL are active fields of research and development.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] Experiments into the processing power required to provide graphics in real time at ultra-high-resolution modes like 4K Ultra HD begun, though beyond reach of all but the highest-end hardware.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] In cinema, most animated movies are CGI now; many animated CGI films are made per year, but few, if any, attempt photorealism due to continuing fears of the uncanny valley.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] In videogames, the Microsoft Xbox One, Sony PlayStation 4, and Nintendo Switch dominated the home space and were all capable of advanced 3D graphics; Windows was still one of the most active gaming platforms as well.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] In the 2020s', advances in ray-tracing technology allowed it to be used for real-time rendering, as well as AI-powered graphics for generating or upscaling frames.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] While ray-tracing existed before, Nvidia was the first to push for ray-tracing with ray-tracing cores, as well as for AI with DLSS and Tensor cores.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] AMD followed suit with the same; FSR, Tensor cores and ray-tracing cores.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] 2D computer graphics are the computer-based generation of digital images—mostly from models, such as digital image, and by techniques specific to them.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] 2D computer graphics are mainly used in applications that were originally developed upon traditional printing and drawing technologies such as typography.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] A large form of digital art, pixel art is created through the use of raster graphics software, where images are edited on the pixel level.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] Graphics in most old (or relatively limited) computer and video games, graphing calculator games, and many mobile phone games are mostly pixel art.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] A sprite is a two-dimensional image or animation that is integrated into a larger scene.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] Initially including just graphical objects handled separately from the memory bitmap of a video display, this now includes various manners of graphical overlays.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] Originally, sprites were a method of integrating unrelated bitmaps so that they appeared to be part of the normal bitmap on a screen, such as creating an animated character that can be moved on a screen without altering the data defining the overall screen.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] Such sprites can be created by either electronic circuitry or software.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] In circuitry, a hardware sprite is a hardware construct that employs custom DMA channels to integrate visual elements with the main screen in that it super-imposes two discrete video sources.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] Software can simulate this through specialized rendering methods.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] Vector graphics formats are complementary to raster graphics.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] Raster graphics is the representation of images as an array of pixels and is typically used for the representation of photographic images.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] Vector graphics consists of encoding information about shapes and colors that comprise the image, which can allow for more flexibility in rendering.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] There are instances when working with vector tools and formats is best practice, and instances when working with raster tools and formats is best practice.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] There are times when both formats come together.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] An understanding of the advantages and limitations of each technology and the relationship between them is most likely to result in efficient and effective use of tools.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] Since the mid-2010s, as a result of advances in deep neural networks, models have been created which take as input a natural language description and produces as output an image matching that description.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] Text-to-image models generally combine a language model, which transforms the input text into a latent representation, and a generative image model, which produces an image conditioned on that representation.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] The most effective models have generally been trained on massive amounts of image and text data scraped from the web.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] By 2022, the best of these models, for example Dall-E 2 and Stable Diffusion, are able to create images in a range of styles, ranging from imitations of living artists to near-photorealistic, in a matter of seconds, given powerful enough hardware.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] 3D graphics, compared to 2D graphics, are graphics that use a three-dimensional representation of geometric data.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] For the purpose of performance, this is stored in the computer.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] This includes images that may be for later display or for real-time viewing.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] Despite these differences, 3D computer graphics rely on similar algorithms as 2D computer graphics do in the frame and raster graphics (like in 2D) in the final rendered display.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] In computer graphics software, the distinction between 2D and 3D is occasionally blurred; 2D applications may use 3D techniques to achieve effects such as lighting, and primarily 3D may use 2D rendering techniques.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] 3D computer graphics are the same as 3D models.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] The model is contained within the graphical data file, apart from the rendering.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] However, there are differences that include the 3D model being the representation of any 3D object.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] Until visually displayed, a model is not graphic.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] Due to printing, 3D models are not only confined to virtual space.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] 3D rendering is how a model can be displayed.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] Also can be used in non-graphical computer simulations and calculations.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] Computer animation is the art of creating moving images via the use of computers.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] It is a subfield of computer graphics and animation.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] Increasingly it is created by means of 3D computer graphics, though 2D computer graphics are still widely used for stylistic, low bandwidth, and faster real-time rendering needs.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] Sometimes the target of the animation is the computer itself, but sometimes the target is another medium, such as film.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] It is also referred to as CGI (Computer-generated imagery or computer-generated imaging), especially when used in films.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] Virtual entities may contain and be controlled by assorted attributes, such as transform values (location, orientation, and scale) stored in an object's transformation matrix.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] Animation is the change of an attribute over time.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] Multiple methods of achieving animation exist; the rudimentary form is based on the creation and editing of keyframes, each storing a value at a given time, per attribute to be animated.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] The 2D/3D graphics software will change with each keyframe, creating an editable curve of a value mapped over time, in which results in animation.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] To create the illusion of movement, an image is displayed on the computer screen then quickly replaced by a new image that is similar to the previous image, but shifted slightly.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] This technique is identical to the illusion of movement in television and motion pictures.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] Images are typically created by devices such as cameras, mirrors, lenses, telescopes, microscopes, etc.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] Digital images include both vector images and raster images, but raster images are more commonly used.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] In digital imaging, a pixel (or picture element) is a single point in a raster image.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] Pixels are placed on a regular 2-dimensional grid, and are often represented using dots or squares.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] Each pixel is a sample of an original image, where more samples typically provide a more accurate representation of the original.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] The intensity of each pixel is variable; in color systems, each pixel typically has three subpixels such as red, green, and blue.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] Graphics are visual representations on a surface, such as a computer screen.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] Examples are photographs, drawing, graphics designs, maps, engineering drawings, or other images.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] Graphics often combine text and illustration.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] Graphic design may consist of the deliberate selection, creation, or arrangement of typography alone, as in a brochure, flier, poster, web site, or book without any other element.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] Clarity or effective communication may be the objective, association with other cultural elements may be sought, or merely, the creation of a distinctive style.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] Primitives are basic units which a graphics system may combine to create more complex images or models.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] Examples would be sprites and character maps in 2D video games, geometric primitives in CAD, or polygons or triangles in 3D rendering.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] Primitives may be supported in hardware for efficient rendering, or the building blocks provided by a graphics application.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] Rendering is the generation of a 2D image from a 3D model by means of computer programs.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] A scene file contains objects in a strictly defined language or data structure; it would contain geometry, viewpoint, texturing, lighting, and shading information as a description of the virtual scene.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] The data contained in the scene file is then passed to a rendering program to be processed and output to a digital image or raster graphics image file.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] The rendering program is usually built into the computer graphics software, though others are available as plug-ins or entirely separate programs.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] The term "rendering" may be by analogy with an "artist's rendering" of a scene.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] Although the technical details of rendering methods vary, the general challenges to overcome in producing a 2D image from a 3D representation stored in a scene file are outlined as the graphics pipeline along a rendering device, such as a GPU.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] A GPU is a device able to assist the CPU in calculations.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] If a scene is to look relatively realistic and predictable under virtual lighting, the rendering software should solve the rendering equation.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] The rendering equation does not account for all lighting phenomena, but is a general lighting model for computer-generated imagery.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] 'Rendering' is also used to describe the process of calculating effects in a video editing file to produce final video output.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] is a method of mapping three dimensional points to a two dimensional plane.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] As most current methods for displaying graphical data are based on planar two dimensional media, the use of this type of projection is widespread.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] It is a process used in drawing for depicting levels of darkness on paper by applying media more densely or with a darker shade for darker areas, and less densely or with a lighter shade for lighter areas.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] where perpendicular lines of varying closeness are drawn in a grid pattern to shade an area.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] The closer the lines are together, the darker the area appears.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] Likewise, the farther apart the lines are, the lighter the area appears.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] A texture map is applied (mapped) to the surface of a shape, or polygon.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] This process is akin to applying patterned paper to a plain white box.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] Multitexturing is the use of more than one texture at a time on a polygon.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] to simulate mirror-like reflectivity, also called gloss.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] Anti-aliasing methods rectify such problems, resulting in imagery more pleasing to the viewer, but can be somewhat computationally expensive.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] ) are able to be employed, then customized for the most efficient rendering performance versus quality of the resultant imagery; a graphics artist should consider this trade-off if anti-aliasing methods are to be used.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] help to solve texture-related aliasing problems.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] Volume rendering is a technique used to display a 2D projection of a 3D discretely sampled data set.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] A typical 3D data set is a group of 2D slice images acquired by a CT or MRI scanner.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] Usually these are acquired in a regular pattern (e.g., one slice every millimeter) and usually have a regular number of image pixels in a regular pattern.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] This is an example of a regular volumetric grid, with each volume element, or voxel represented by a single value that is obtained by sampling the immediate area surrounding the voxel.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] 3D modeling is the process of developing a mathematical, wireframe representation of any three-dimensional object, called a "3D model", via specialized software.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] Models may be created automatically or manually; the manual modeling process of preparing geometric data for 3D computer graphics is similar to plastic arts such as sculpting.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] 3D models may be created using multiple approaches: use of NURBs to generate accurate and smooth surface patches, polygonal mesh modeling (manipulation of faceted geometry), or polygonal mesh subdivision (advanced tessellation of polygons, resulting in smooth surfaces similar to NURB models).
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] A 3D model can be displayed as a two-dimensional image through a process called *3D rendering*, used in a computer simulation of physical phenomena, or animated directly for other purposes.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p01] The model can also be physically created using 3D Printing devices.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p02] was a pioneer in computer animation and digital fine art and created the first computer art in 1964.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p02] is a leading innovator in computer graphics.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p02] Greenberg was the founding director of the NSF Center for Computer Graphics and Scientific Visualization.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p02] He began creating digital art in 1962, making him one of the earliest digital artists.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p02] is a former professor of computer science.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p02] The study of computer graphics is a sub-field of computer science which studies methods for digitally synthesizing and manipulating visual content.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p02] Although the term often refers to three-dimensional computer graphics, it also encompasses two-dimensional graphics and image processing.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p02] As an academic discipline, computer graphics studies the manipulation of visual and geometric information using computational techniques.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p02] It focuses on the *mathematical* and *computational* foundations of image generation and processing rather than purely aesthetic issues.
[src:graphics/computer-graphics-p02] Computer graphics is often differentiated from the field of visualization, although the two fields have many similarities.
[src:graphics/global-illumination] Areas that lie outside of the ceiling lamp's direct light lack definition.
[src:graphics/global-illumination] For example, the lamp's housing appears completely uniform.
[src:graphics/global-illumination] Without the ambient light added into the render, it would appear uniformly black.
[src:graphics/global-illumination] Light is reflected by surfaces, and colored light transfers from one surface to another.
[src:graphics/global-illumination] Notice how color from the red wall and green wall (not visible) reflects onto other surfaces in the scene.
[src:graphics/global-illumination] projected onto the red wall from light passing through the glass sphere.
[src:graphics/global-illumination] Theoretically, reflections, refractions, transparency, and shadows are all examples of global illumination, because when simulating them, one object affects the rendering of another (as opposed to an object being affected only by a direct source of light).
[src:graphics/global-illumination] In practice, however, only the simulation of diffuse inter-reflection or caustics is called global illumination, especially in real-time settings.
[src:graphics/global-illumination] Global illumination is a key aspect to the realism of a 3D scene.
[src:graphics/global-illumination] Naive 3D lighting will only take into account direct light, meaning any light which radiates off a light source and bounces directly into the virtual camera.
[src:graphics/global-illumination] Shadows will appear completely dark, due to light not interacting with any other surface before it reaches the camera.
[src:graphics/global-illumination] As this is not what occurs in real life, we perceive the resulting image as incomplete.
[src:graphics/global-illumination] Applying full global illumination allows for the missing effects that makes an image feel more natural.
[src:graphics/global-illumination] However, global illumination is computationally more expensive and consequently much slower to generate.
[src:graphics/global-illumination] The algorithms used to calculate the distribution of light energy between surfaces of a scene are closely related to heat transfer simulations performed using finite-element methods in engineering design.
[src:graphics/global-illumination] Achieving accurate computation of global illumination in real-time remains difficult.
[src:graphics/global-illumination] On one end, the diffuse inter-reflection component of global illumination is sometimes approximated by an "ambient" term in the lighting equation, which is also called "ambient lighting" or "ambient color" in 3D software.
[src:graphics/global-illumination] Though this method is one of the cheapest ways to simulate indirect lighting, when used alone it does not provide an adequately realistic effect.
[src:graphics/global-illumination] Ambient lighting is known to "flatten" shadows in 3D scenes, making the overall visual effect more bland.
[src:graphics/global-illumination] Beyond ambient lighting, techniques which trace the path of light accurately have historically been either too slow for consumer hardware or limited to static and precomputed environments.
[src:graphics/global-illumination] This proves problematic, as most applications allow for input from a user that can affect their surroundings, and the precalculation steps may introduce constraints upon the artists.
[src:graphics/global-illumination] Consequently, research has been dedicated to finding a balance between adequate performance, accurate visual results, and interactivity.
[src:graphics/global-illumination] Starting with Nvidia's RTX 20 series, consumer graphics hardware has been extended to allow for ray tracing computations to be performed in real time through hardware acceleration.
[src:graphics/global-illumination] This has allowed for further improvements, as applications can now harness the power of this acceleration to provide not only precise lighting results, but the ability to affect said lighting dynamically.
[src:graphics/global-illumination] Some content that has taken advantage of this capability includes Cyberpunk 2077, Indiana Jones and the Great Circle, and Alan Wake 2, among others.
[src:graphics/global-illumination] For an overview of the current state of real-time global illumination, see or.
[src:graphics/global-illumination] Algorithms which attempt to simulate global illumination are numerical approximations of the rendering equation.
[src:graphics/global-illumination] Well-known algorithms for computing global illumination include path tracing, photon mapping and radiosity.
[src:graphics/graphics-pipeline] The **computer graphics pipeline**, or simply **graphics pipeline**, also known as the **rendering pipeline**, is a series of procedures for transforming a three-dimensional (3D) scene into a two-dimensional (2D) representation on a screen.
[src:graphics/graphics-pipeline] Once a 3D model is generated, the 3D computer graphics pipeline converts the model into a visually perceivable format on the computer display.
[src:graphics/graphics-pipeline] Due to the dependence on specific software and hardware configurations and desired display attributes, a universally applicable graphics pipeline does not exist.
[src:graphics/graphics-pipeline] Nevertheless, graphics application programming interfaces (APIs), such as Direct3D, OpenGL and Vulkan were developed to standardize common procedures and oversee the graphics pipeline of a given hardware accelerator.
[src:graphics/graphics-pipeline] These APIs provide an abstraction layer over the underlying hardware, relieving programmers from the need to write code explicitly targeting various graphics hardware accelerators like AMD, Intel, Nvidia, and others.
[src:graphics/graphics-pipeline] The model of the graphics pipeline is usually used in real-time rendering.
[src:graphics/graphics-pipeline] Often, most of the pipeline steps are implemented in hardware, which allows for special optimizations.
[src:graphics/graphics-pipeline] The term "pipeline" is used in a similar sense for the pipeline in processors: the individual steps of the pipeline often run in parallel when a given stage has enough data.
[src:graphics/graphics-pipeline] The 3D pipeline usually refers to the most common form of computer 3-dimensional rendering called 3D polygon rendering, distinct from raytracing and raycasting.
[src:graphics/graphics-pipeline] In raycasting, a ray originates at the point where the camera resides, and if that ray hits a surface, the color and lighting of the point on the surface where the ray hit is calculated.
[src:graphics/graphics-pipeline] In 3D polygon rendering the reverse happens – the area that is given the camera is calculated and then rays are created from every part of every surface given the camera and traced back to the camera.
[src:graphics/graphics-pipeline] A graphics pipeline can be divided into three main parts: Application, Geometry, and Rasterization.
[src:graphics/graphics-pipeline] The application step is executed by the software or hardware on the main processors (CPU, GPU).
[src:graphics/graphics-pipeline] During the application step, changes are made to the scene as required, for example, by user interaction using input devices or during an animation.
[src:graphics/graphics-pipeline] The new scene with the modified primitives (points, lines, triangles, etc.) is then passed on to the next step in the pipeline.
[src:graphics/graphics-pipeline] Examples of application step are collision detection, animation, morphing, and acceleration techniques using spatial subdivision schemes such as quadtrees or octrees.
[src:graphics/graphics-pipeline] These are also used to reduce the amount of main memory required at a given time.
[src:graphics/graphics-pipeline] The "world" of a modern computer game is usually larger than available onboard memory.
[src:graphics/graphics-pipeline] The geometry pipeline and the vertex pipeline are responsible for most of the operations with polygons.
[src:graphics/graphics-pipeline] These can be further divided into the five tasks.
[src:graphics/graphics-pipeline] How these tasks are organized as actual parallel pipeline steps is implementation specific.
[src:graphics/graphics-pipeline] The world coordinate system is the coordinate system in which the virtual world is created.
[src:graphics/graphics-pipeline] The objects contained within the scene (houses, trees, cars) are often designed in their object coordinate system (also called model coordinate system or local coordinate system) for reasons of simpler modelling.
[src:graphics/graphics-pipeline] To assign these objects to coordinates in the world coordinate system or global coordinate system of the entire scene, the object coordinates are transformed using translation, rotation, or scaling.
[src:graphics/graphics-pipeline] This is done by multiplying the corresponding transformation matrices.
[src:graphics/graphics-pipeline] In addition, several differently transformed copies can be formed from one object, for example, a forest from a tree.
[src:graphics/graphics-pipeline] In addition to the objects, the scene also defines a virtual camera or viewer that indicates the position and direction of view relative to which the scene is rendered.
[src:graphics/graphics-pipeline] The scene is transformed so that the camera is at the origin looking along the Z-axis.
[src:graphics/graphics-pipeline] The resulting coordinate system is called the camera coordinate system and the transformation is called *camera transformation* or *View Transformation*.
[src:graphics/graphics-pipeline] The 3D projection step transforms the view volume into a cube with the corner point coordinates (−1, −1, 0) and (1, 1, 1); Occasionally other target volumes are also used.
[src:graphics/graphics-pipeline] This step is called *projection*, even though it transforms a volume into another volume, since the resulting Z coordinates are not stored in the image, but are only used in Z-buffering in the later rastering step.
[src:graphics/graphics-pipeline] In a perspective illustration, a central projection is used.
[src:graphics/graphics-pipeline] To limit the number of displayed objects, two additional clipping planes are used; The visual volume is therefore a truncated pyramid (frustum).
[src:graphics/graphics-pipeline] The parallel or orthogonal projection is used, for example, for technical representations because it has the advantage that all parallels in the object space are also parallel in the image space, and the surfaces and volumes are the same size regardless of the distance from the viewer.
[src:graphics/graphics-pipeline] For reasons of efficiency, the camera and projection matrix are usually combined into a transformation matrix so that the camera coordinate system is omitted.
[src:graphics/graphics-pipeline] The resulting matrix is usually the same for a single image, while the world matrix looks different for each object.
[src:graphics/graphics-pipeline] In practice, therefore, view and projection are pre-calculated so that only the world matrix has to be adapted during the display.
[src:graphics/graphics-pipeline] However, more complex transformations such as vertex blending are possible.
[src:graphics/graphics-pipeline] Freely programmable geometry shaders that modify the geometry can also be executed.
[src:graphics/graphics-pipeline] In the actual rendering step, the world matrix * camera matrix * projection matrix is calculated and then finally applied to every single point.
[src:graphics/graphics-pipeline] Thus, the points of all objects are transferred directly to the screen coordinate system (at least almost, the value range of the axes is still −1..1 for the visible range, see section "Window-Viewport-Transformation").
[src:graphics/graphics-pipeline] Often a scene contains light sources placed at different positions to make the lighting of the objects appear more realistic.
[src:graphics/graphics-pipeline] In this case, a gain factor for the texture is calculated for each vertex based on the light sources and the material properties associated with the corresponding triangle.
[src:graphics/graphics-pipeline] In the later rasterization step, the vertex values of a triangle are interpolated over its surface.
[src:graphics/graphics-pipeline] A general lighting (ambient light) is applied to all surfaces.
[src:graphics/graphics-pipeline] It is the diffuse and thus direction-independent brightness of the scene.
[src:graphics/graphics-pipeline] The sun is a directed light source, which can be assumed to be infinitely far away.
[src:graphics/graphics-pipeline] The illumination effected by the sun on a surface is determined by forming the scalar product of the directional vector from the sun and the normal vector of the surface.
[src:graphics/graphics-pipeline] If the value is negative, the surface is facing the sun.
[src:graphics/graphics-pipeline] Only the primitives that are within the visual volume need to be rastered (drawn).
[src:graphics/graphics-pipeline] This visual volume is defined as the inside of a frustum, a shape in the form of a pyramid with a cut-off top.
[src:graphics/graphics-pipeline] Primitives that are completely outside the visual volume are discarded; This is called frustum culling.
[src:graphics/graphics-pipeline] Further culling methods such as back-face culling, which reduces the number of primitives to be considered, can theoretically be executed in any step of the graphics pipeline.
[src:graphics/graphics-pipeline] Primitives that are only partially inside the cube must be clipped against the cube.
[src:graphics/graphics-pipeline] The advantage of the previous projection step is that the clipping always takes place against the same cube.
[src:graphics/graphics-pipeline] Only the – possibly clipped – primitives, which are within the visual volume, are forwarded to the final step.
[src:graphics/graphics-pipeline] To output the image to any target area (viewport) of the screen, another transformation, the *Window-Viewport transformation*, must be applied.
[src:graphics/graphics-pipeline] The resulting coordinates are the device coordinates of the output device.
[src:graphics/graphics-pipeline] On modern hardware, most of the geometry computation steps are performed in the vertex shader.
[src:graphics/graphics-pipeline] This is, in principle, freely programmable, but generally performs at least the transformation of the points and the illumination calculation.
[src:graphics/graphics-pipeline] For the DirectX programming interface, the use of a custom vertex shader is necessary from version 10, while older versions still have a standard shader.
[src:graphics/graphics-pipeline] The rasterization step is the final step before the fragment shader pipeline that all primitives are rasterized with.
[src:graphics/graphics-pipeline] In the rasterization step, discrete fragments are created from continuous primitives.
[src:graphics/graphics-pipeline] In this stage of the graphics pipeline, the grid points are also called fragments, for the sake of greater distinctiveness.
[src:graphics/graphics-pipeline] Each fragment corresponds to one pixel in the frame buffer and this corresponds to one pixel of the screen.
[src:graphics/graphics-pipeline] These can be colored (and possibly illuminated).
[src:graphics/graphics-pipeline] Furthermore, it is necessary to determine the visible, closer to the observer fragment, in the case of overlapping polygons.
[src:graphics/graphics-pipeline] A Z-buffer is usually used for this so-called hidden surface determination.
[src:graphics/graphics-pipeline] The color of a fragment depends on the illumination, texture, and other material properties of the visible primitive and is often interpolated using the triangle vertex properties.
[src:graphics/graphics-pipeline] Where available, a fragment shader (also called Pixel Shader) is run in the rastering step for each fragment of the object.
[src:graphics/graphics-pipeline] If a fragment is visible, it can now be mixed with already existing color values in the image if transparency or multi-sampling is used.
[src:graphics/graphics-pipeline] In this step, one or more fragments become a pixel.
[src:graphics/graphics-pipeline] To prevent the user from seeing the gradual rasterization of the primitives, double buffering takes place.
[src:graphics/graphics-pipeline] The rasterization is carried out in a special memory area.
[src:graphics/graphics-pipeline] Once the image has been completely rasterized, it is copied to the visible area of the image memory.
[src:graphics/graphics-pipeline] All matrices used are nonsingular and thus invertible.
[src:graphics/graphics-pipeline] Since the multiplication of two nonsingular matrices creates another nonsingular matrix, the entire transformation matrix is also invertible.
[src:graphics/graphics-pipeline] The inverse is required to recalculate world coordinates from screen coordinates – for example, to determine from the mouse pointer position the clicked object.
[src:graphics/graphics-pipeline] However, since the screen and the mouse have only two dimensions, the third is unknown.
[src:graphics/graphics-pipeline] Therefore, a ray is projected at the cursor position into the world and then the intersection of this ray with the polygons in the world is determined.
[src:graphics/phong-shading] In 3D computer graphics, **Phong shading, Phong interpolation,** or **normal-vector interpolation shading** is an interpolation technique for surface shading invented by computer graphics pioneer Bui Tuong Phong.
[src:graphics/phong-shading] Phong shading interpolates surface normals across rasterized polygons and computes pixel colors based on the interpolated normals and a reflection model.
[src:graphics/phong-shading] *Phong shading* may also refer to the specific combination of Phong interpolation and the Phong reflection model.
[src:graphics/phong-shading] Phong shading and the Phong reflection model were developed at the University of Utah by Bui Tuong Phong, who published them in his 1973 Ph.D. dissertation and a 1975 paper.
[src:graphics/phong-shading] Phong's methods were considered radical at the time of their introduction, but have since become the *de facto* baseline shading method for many rendering applications.
[src:graphics/phong-shading] Phong's methods have proven popular due to their generally efficient use of computation time per rendered pixel.
[src:graphics/phong-shading] Phong shading improves upon Gouraud shading and provides a better approximation of the shading of a smooth surface.
[src:graphics/phong-shading] Phong shading assumes a smoothly varying surface normal vector.
[src:graphics/phong-shading] The Phong interpolation method works better than Gouraud shading when applied to a reflection model with small specular highlights such as the Phong reflection model.
[src:graphics/phong-shading] The most serious problem with Gouraud shading occurs when specular highlights are found in the middle of a large polygon.
[src:graphics/phong-shading] Since these specular highlights are absent from the polygon's vertices and Gouraud shading interpolates based on the vertex colors, the specular highlight will be missing from the polygon's interior.
[src:graphics/phong-shading] Unlike Gouraud shading, which interpolates colors across polygons, in Phong shading, a normal vector is linearly interpolated across the surface of the polygon from the polygon's vertex normals.
[src:graphics/phong-shading] The surface normal is interpolated and normalized at each pixel and then used in a reflection model, e.g. the Phong reflection model, to obtain the final pixel color.
[src:graphics/phong-shading] Phong shading is more computationally expensive than Gouraud shading since the reflection model must be computed at each pixel instead of at each vertex.
[src:graphics/phong-shading] In modern graphics hardware, variants of this algorithm are implemented using pixel or fragment shaders.
[src:graphics/rasterisation] In computer graphics, **rasterisation** (British English) or **rasterization** (American English) is the task of taking an image described in a vector graphics format (shapes) and converting it into a raster image which represents the original image.
[src:graphics/rasterisation] The rasterized image may then be displayed on a computer display, video display or printer, or stored in a bitmap file format.
[src:graphics/rasterisation] Rasterization may refer to the technique of drawing 3D models, or to the conversion of 2D rendering primitives, such as polygons and line segments, into a rasterized format.
[src:graphics/rasterisation] The term "rasterisation" comes from German *Raster* 'grid, pattern, schema' and Latin *rāstrum* 'scraper, rake'.
[src:graphics/rasterisation] Bresenham's line algorithm is an example of an algorithm used to rasterize lines.
[src:graphics/rasterisation] Algorithms such as the midpoint circle algorithm are used to render circles onto a pixelated canvas.
[src:graphics/rasterisation] Polygons are a common representation of digital 3D models.
[src:graphics/rasterisation] Before rasterization, individual polygons are triangulated - therefore, a typical problem to solve in 3D rasterization is rasterization of a triangle.
[src:graphics/rasterisation] 2. no pixel is rasterized more than once, i.e. the rasterized triangles don't overlap.
[src:graphics/rasterisation] This is to guarantee that the result doesn't depend on the order in which the triangles are rasterized.
[src:graphics/rasterisation] Overdrawing pixels can also mean wasting computing power on pixels that would be overwritten.
[src:graphics/rasterisation] This leads to establishing **rasterization rules** to guarantee the above conditions.
[src:graphics/rasterisation] 2. its center lies exactly on the triangle edge (or multiple edges in case of corners) – that is (or, in case of corners, all are), either the *top* or *left* edge.
[src:graphics/rasterisation] A *top* edge is an edge that is exactly horizontal and lies above other edges, and a *left* edge is a non-horizontal edge that is on the left side of the triangle.
[src:graphics/rasterisation] This rule decides which triangle a pixel on a boundary belongs to.
[src:graphics/rasterisation] It is implemented by Direct3D and OpenGL (although the specification here only requires a consistent rule).
[src:graphics/rasterisation] Rasterization is one of the typical techniques of rendering 3D models.
[src:graphics/rasterisation] Compared with other rendering techniques such as ray tracing, rasterization is extremely fast and therefore used in most realtime 3D engines.
[src:graphics/rasterisation] However, rasterization is simply the process of computing the mapping from scene geometry to pixels and does not prescribe a particular way to compute the color of those pixels.
[src:graphics/rasterisation] The specific color of each pixel is assigned by a pixel shader (which in modern GPUs is completely programmable).
[src:graphics/rasterisation] Shading may take into account physical effects such as light position, their approximations or purely artistic intent.
[src:graphics/rasterisation] The process of rasterizing 3D models onto a 2D plane for display on a computer screen ("screen space") is often carried out by fixed function (non-programmable) hardware within the graphics pipeline.
[src:graphics/rasterisation] This is because there is no motivation for modifying the techniques for rasterization used at render time and a special-purpose system allows for high efficiency.
[src:graphics/rasterisation] The quality of rasterization can be improved by antialiasing, which creates "smooth" edges.
[src:graphics/rasterisation] Sub-pixel precision is a method which takes into account positions on a finer scale than the pixel grid and can produce different results even if the endpoints of a primitive fall into same pixel coordinates, producing smoother movement animations.
[src:graphics/rasterisation] Simple or older hardware, such as PlayStation 1, lacked sub-pixel precision in 3D rasterization.
[src:graphics/ray-tracing-graphics] In 3D computer graphics, **ray tracing** is a technique for modeling light transport for use in a wide variety of rendering algorithms for generating digital images.
[src:graphics/ray-tracing-graphics] On a spectrum of computational cost and visual fidelity, ray tracing-based rendering techniques, such as ray casting, recursive ray tracing, distribution ray tracing, photon mapping and path tracing, are generally slower and higher fidelity than scanline rendering methods.
[src:graphics/ray-tracing-graphics] Ray tracing is capable of simulating a variety of optical effects, such as reflection, refraction, soft shadows, scattering, depth of field, motion blur, caustics, ambient occlusion and dispersion phenomena (such as chromatic aberration).
[src:graphics/ray-tracing-graphics] It can also be used to trace the path of sound waves in a similar fashion to light waves, making it a viable option for more immersive sound design in video games by rendering realistic reverberation and echoes.
[src:graphics/ray-tracing-graphics] In fact, any physical wave or particle phenomenon with approximately linear motion can be simulated with ray tracing.
[src:graphics/ray-tracing-graphics] Ray tracing–based rendering techniques that sample light over a domain typically generate multiple rays and often rely on denoising to reduce the resulting noise.
[src:graphics/ray-tracing-graphics] The idea of ray tracing comes from as early as the 16th century, when it was described by Albrecht Dürer, who is credited for its invention.
[src:graphics/ray-tracing-graphics] Dürer described multiple techniques for projecting 3-D scenes onto an image plane.
[src:graphics/ray-tracing-graphics] Some of these project chosen geometry onto the image plane, as is done with rasterization today.
[src:graphics/ray-tracing-graphics] Others determine what geometry is visible along a given ray, as is done with ray tracing.
[src:graphics/ray-tracing-graphics] Using a computer for ray tracing to generate shaded pictures was first accomplished by Arthur Appel in 1968.
[src:graphics/ray-tracing-graphics] Appel used ray tracing for primary visibility (determining the closest surface to the camera at each image point) by tracing a ray through each point to be shaded into the scene to identify the visible surface.
[src:graphics/ray-tracing-graphics] The closest surface intersected by the ray was the visible one.
[src:graphics/ray-tracing-graphics] This non-recursive ray tracing-based rendering algorithm is today called "ray casting".
[src:graphics/ray-tracing-graphics] His algorithm then traced secondary rays to the light source from each point being shaded to determine whether the point was in shadow or not.
[src:graphics/ray-tracing-graphics] Later, in 1971, Goldstein and Nagel of MAGI (Mathematical Applications Group, Inc.) published "3-D Visual Simulation", wherein ray tracing was used to make shaded pictures of solids.
[src:graphics/ray-tracing-graphics] At the ray-surface intersection point found, they computed the surface normal and, knowing the position of the light source, computed the brightness of the pixel on the screen.
[src:graphics/ray-tracing-graphics] Their publication describes a short (30-second) film "made using the University of Maryland's display hardware outfitted with a 16mm camera.
[src:graphics/ray-tracing-graphics] The film showed the helicopter and a simple ground-level gun emplacement.
[src:graphics/ray-tracing-graphics] The helicopter was programmed to undergo a series of maneuvers including turns, take-offs, and landings, etc., until it eventually is shot down and crashed." A *CDC 6600* computer was used.
[src:graphics/ray-tracing-graphics] MAGI produced an animation video called *MAGI/SynthaVision Sampler* in 1974.
[src:graphics/ray-tracing-graphics] Another early instance of ray casting came in 1976, when Scott Roth created a flip book animation in Bob Sproull's computer graphics course at Caltech.
[src:graphics/ray-tracing-graphics] The scanned pages are shown as a video in the accompanying image.
[src:graphics/ray-tracing-graphics] Roth's computer program noted an edge point at a pixel location if the ray intersected a bounded plane different from that of its neighbors.
[src:graphics/ray-tracing-graphics] Of course, a ray could intersect multiple planes in space, but only the surface point closest to the camera was noted as visible.
[src:graphics/ray-tracing-graphics] The platform was a DEC PDP-10, a Tektronix storage-tube display, and a printer which would create an image of the display on rolling thermal paper.
[src:graphics/ray-tracing-graphics] Roth extended the framework, introduced the term *ray casting* in the context of computer graphics and solid modeling, and in 1982 published his work while at GM Research Labs.
[src:graphics/ray-tracing-graphics] Turner Whitted was the first to show recursive ray tracing for mirror reflection and for refraction through translucent objects, with an angle determined by the solid's index of refraction, and to use ray tracing for anti-aliasing.
[src:graphics/ray-tracing-graphics] He produced a recursive ray traced film called *The Compleat Angler* in 1979 while an engineer at Bell Labs.
[src:graphics/ray-tracing-graphics] Whitted's deeply recursive ray tracing algorithm reframed rendering from being primarily a matter of surface visibility determination to being a matter of light transport.
[src:graphics/ray-tracing-graphics] His paper inspired a series of subsequent work by others that included distribution ray tracing and finally unbiased path tracing, which provides the *rendering equation* framework that has allowed computer-generated imagery to be faithful to reality.
[src:graphics/ray-tracing-graphics] For decades, global illumination in major films using computer-generated imagery was approximated with additional lights.
[src:graphics/ray-tracing-graphics] Ray tracing-based rendering eventually changed that by enabling physically based light transport.
[src:graphics/ray-tracing-graphics] Early feature films rendered entirely using path tracing include *Monster House* (2006), *Cloudy with a Chance of Meatballs* (2009), and *Monsters University* (2013).
[src:graphics/ray-tracing-graphics] Optical ray tracing describes a method for producing visual images constructed in 3D computer graphics environments, with more photorealism than either ray casting or scanline rendering techniques.
[src:graphics/ray-tracing-graphics] It works by tracing a path from an imaginary eye through each pixel in a virtual screen, and calculating the color of the object visible through it.
[src:graphics/ray-tracing-graphics] Scenes in ray tracing are described mathematically by a programmer or by a visual artist (normally using intermediary tools).
[src:graphics/ray-tracing-graphics] Scenes may also incorporate data from images and models captured by means such as digital photography.
[src:graphics/ray-tracing-graphics] Typically, each ray must be tested for intersection with some subset of all the objects in the scene.
[src:graphics/ray-tracing-graphics] Once the nearest object has been identified, the algorithm will estimate the incoming light at the point of intersection, examine the material properties of the object, and combine this information to calculate the final color of the pixel.
[src:graphics/ray-tracing-graphics] Certain illumination algorithms and reflective or translucent materials may require more rays to be re-cast into the scene.
[src:graphics/ray-tracing-graphics] It may at first seem counterintuitive or "backward" to send rays *away* from the camera, rather than *into* it (as actual light does in reality), but doing so is many orders of magnitude more efficient.
[src:graphics/ray-tracing-graphics] Since the overwhelming majority of light rays from a given light source do not make it directly into the viewer's eye, a "forward" simulation could potentially waste a tremendous amount of computation on light paths that are never recorded.
[src:graphics/ray-tracing-graphics] Therefore, the shortcut taken in ray tracing is to presuppose that a given ray intersects the view frame.
[src:graphics/ray-tracing-graphics] After either a maximum number of reflections or a ray traveling a certain distance without intersection, the ray ceases to travel and the pixel's value is updated.
[src:graphics/ray-tracing-graphics] The idea is to find the position of each viewport pixel center $P_{ij}$ which allows us to find the line going from eye E through that pixel and finally get the ray described by point E and vector ${\vec {R}}_{ij}=P_{ij}-E$ (or its normalization ${\vec {r}}_{ij}$ ).
[src:graphics/ray-tracing-graphics] First we need to find the coordinates of the bottom left viewport pixel $P_{1m}$ and find the next pixel by making a shift along directions parallel to viewport (vectors ${\vec {b}}_{n}$ , ${\vec {v}}_{n}$ ) multiplied by the size of the pixel.
[src:graphics/ray-tracing-graphics] Below we introduce formulas which include distance d between the eye and the viewport.
[src:graphics/ray-tracing-graphics] However, this value will be reduced during ray normalization ${\vec {r}}_{ij}$ (so you might as well accept that $d=1$ and remove it from calculations).
[src:graphics/ray-tracing-graphics] In nature, a light source emits a ray of light which travels, eventually, to a surface that interrupts its progress.
[src:graphics/ray-tracing-graphics] One can think of this "ray" as a stream of photons traveling along the same path.
[src:graphics/ray-tracing-graphics] In a perfect vacuum this ray will be a straight line (ignoring relativistic effects).
[src:graphics/ray-tracing-graphics] Any combination of four things might happen with this light ray: absorption, reflection, refraction and fluorescence.
[src:graphics/ray-tracing-graphics] A surface may absorb part of the light ray, resulting in a loss of intensity of the reflected and/or refracted light.
[src:graphics/ray-tracing-graphics] It might also reflect all or part of the light ray, in one or more directions.
[src:graphics/ray-tracing-graphics] If the surface has any transparent or translucent properties, it refracts a portion of the light beam into itself in a different direction while absorbing some (or all) of the spectrum (and possibly altering the color).
[src:graphics/ray-tracing-graphics] Less commonly, a surface may absorb some portion of the light and fluorescently re-emit the light at a longer wavelength color in a random direction, though this is rare enough that it can be discounted from most rendering applications.
[src:graphics/ray-tracing-graphics] Between absorption, reflection, refraction and fluorescence, all of the incoming light must be accounted for, and no more.
[src:graphics/ray-tracing-graphics] A surface cannot, for instance, reflect 66% of an incoming light ray, and refract 50%, since the two would add up to be 116%.
[src:graphics/ray-tracing-graphics] From here, the reflected and/or refracted rays may strike other surfaces, where their absorptive, refractive, reflective and fluorescent properties again affect the progress of the incoming rays.
[src:graphics/ray-tracing-graphics] Some of these rays travel in such a way that they hit our eye, causing us to see the scene and so contribute to the final rendered image.
[src:graphics/ray-tracing-graphics] The idea behind ray casting, the predecessor to recursive ray tracing, is to trace rays from the eye, one per pixel, and find the closest object blocking the path of that ray.
[src:graphics/ray-tracing-graphics] Think of an image as a screen-door, with each square in the screen being a pixel.
[src:graphics/ray-tracing-graphics] This is then the object the eye sees through that pixel.
[src:graphics/ray-tracing-graphics] Using the material properties and the effect of the lights in the scene, this algorithm can determine the shading of this object.
[src:graphics/ray-tracing-graphics] The simplifying assumption is made that if a surface faces a light, the light will reach that surface and not be blocked or in shadow.
[src:graphics/ray-tracing-graphics] The shading of the surface is computed using traditional 3-D computer graphics shading models.
[src:graphics/ray-tracing-graphics] One important advantage ray casting offered over older scanline algorithms was its ability to easily deal with non-planar surfaces and solids, such as cones and spheres.
[src:graphics/ray-tracing-graphics] If a mathematical surface can be intersected by a ray, it can be rendered using ray casting.
[src:graphics/ray-tracing-graphics] Elaborate objects can be created by using solid modeling techniques and easily rendered.
[src:graphics/ray-tracing-graphics] In the method of volume ray casting, each ray is traced so that color and/or density can be sampled along the ray and then be combined into a final pixel color.
[src:graphics/ray-tracing-graphics] This is often used when objects cannot be easily represented by explicit surfaces (such as triangles), for example when rendering clouds or 3-D medical scans.
[src:graphics/ray-tracing-graphics] In SDF ray marching, or sphere tracing, each ray is traced in multiple steps to approximate an intersection point between the ray and a surface defined by a signed distance function (SDF).
[src:graphics/ray-tracing-graphics] The SDF is evaluated for each iteration in order to be able take as large steps as possible without missing any part of the surface.
[src:graphics/ray-tracing-graphics] A threshold is used to cancel further iteration when a point is reached that is close enough to the surface.
[src:graphics/ray-tracing-graphics] This method is often used for 3-D fractal rendering.
[src:graphics/ray-tracing-graphics] Earlier algorithms traced rays from the eye into the scene until they hit an object, but determined the ray color without recursively tracing more rays.
[src:graphics/ray-tracing-graphics] Recursive ray tracing continues the process.
[src:graphics/ray-tracing-graphics] These recursive rays add more realism to ray traced images.
[src:graphics/ray-tracing-graphics] Ray tracing-based rendering's popularity stems from its basis in a realistic simulation of light transport, as compared to other rendering methods, such as rasterization, which focuses more on the realistic simulation of geometry.
[src:graphics/ray-tracing-graphics] Effects such as reflections and shadows, which are difficult to simulate using other algorithms, are a natural result of the ray tracing algorithm.
[src:graphics/ray-tracing-graphics] The computational independence of each ray makes ray tracing amenable to a basic level of parallelization, but the divergence of ray paths makes high utilization under parallelism quite difficult to achieve in practice.
[src:graphics/ray-tracing-graphics] A serious disadvantage of ray tracing is performance, though it can in theory be faster than traditional scanline rendering, depending on scene complexity vs. number of pixels on-screen.
[src:graphics/ray-tracing-graphics] Until the late 2010s, ray tracing in real time was usually considered impossible on consumer hardware for nontrivial tasks.
[src:graphics/ray-tracing-graphics] Scanline algorithms and other algorithms use data coherence to share computations between pixels, while ray tracing normally starts the process anew, treating each eye ray separately.
[src:graphics/ray-tracing-graphics] However, this separation offers other advantages, such as the ability to shoot more rays as needed to perform spatial anti-aliasing and improve image quality where needed.
[src:graphics/ray-tracing-graphics] Whitted-style recursive ray tracing handles interreflection and optical effects such as refraction, but is not generally photorealistic.
[src:graphics/ray-tracing-graphics] Improved realism occurs when the rendering equation is fully evaluated, as the equation conceptually includes every physical effect of light flow.
[src:graphics/ray-tracing-graphics] However, this is infeasible given the computing resources required, and the limitations on geometric and material modeling fidelity.
[src:graphics/ray-tracing-graphics] Path tracing is an algorithm for evaluating the rendering equation and thus gives higher-fidelity simulations of real-world lighting.
[src:graphics/ray-tracing-graphics] The process of shooting rays from the eye to the light source to render an image is sometimes called *backwards ray tracing*, since it is the opposite direction photons actually travel.
[src:graphics/ray-tracing-graphics] However, there is confusion with this terminology.
[src:graphics/ray-tracing-graphics] Early ray tracing was always done from the eye, and early researchers such as James Arvo used the term *backwards ray tracing* to mean shooting rays from the lights and gathering the results.
[src:graphics/ray-tracing-graphics] Therefore, it is clearer to distinguish *eye-based* versus *light-based* ray tracing.
[src:graphics/ray-tracing-graphics] While the direct illumination is generally best sampled using eye-based ray tracing, certain indirect effects can benefit from rays generated from the lights.
[src:graphics/ray-tracing-graphics] Caustics are bright patterns caused by the focusing of light off a wide reflective region onto a narrow area of (near-)diffuse surface.
[src:graphics/ray-tracing-graphics] An algorithm that casts rays directly from lights onto reflective objects, tracing their paths to the eye, will better sample this phenomenon.
[src:graphics/ray-tracing-graphics] This integration of eye-based and light-based rays is often expressed as bidirectional path tracing, in which paths are traced from both the eye and lights, and the paths subsequently joined by a connecting ray after some length.
[src:graphics/ray-tracing-graphics] Photon mapping is another method that uses both light-based and eye-based ray tracing; in an initial pass, energetic photons are traced along rays from the light source so as to compute an estimate of radiant flux as a function of 3-dimensional space (the eponymous photon map itself).
[src:graphics/ray-tracing-graphics] In a subsequent pass, rays are traced from the eye into the scene to determine the visible surfaces, and the photon map is used to estimate the illumination at the visible surface points.
[src:graphics/ray-tracing-graphics] The advantage of photon mapping versus bidirectional path tracing is the ability to achieve significant reuse of photons, reducing computation, at the cost of statistical bias.
[src:graphics/ray-tracing-graphics] In such cases, only a very small subset of paths will transport energy; Metropolis light transport is a method which begins with a random search of the path space, and when energetic paths are found, reuses this information by exploring the nearby space of rays.
[src:graphics/ray-tracing-graphics] To the right is an image showing a simple example of a path of rays recursively generated from the camera (or eye) to the light source using the above algorithm.
[src:graphics/ray-tracing-graphics] A diffuse surface reflects light in all directions.
[src:graphics/ray-tracing-graphics] First, a ray is created at an eyepoint and traced through a pixel and into the scene, where it hits a diffuse surface.
[src:graphics/ray-tracing-graphics] From that surface, the algorithm recursively generates a reflection ray, which is traced through the scene, where it hits another diffuse surface.
[src:graphics/ray-tracing-graphics] Finally, another reflection ray is generated and traced through the scene, where it hits the light source and is absorbed.
[src:graphics/ray-tracing-graphics] The color of the pixel now depends on the colors of the first and second diffuse surfaces and the color of the light emitted from the light source.
[src:graphics/ray-tracing-graphics] For example, if the light source emitted white light and the two diffuse surfaces were blue, then the resulting color of the pixel is blue.
[src:graphics/ray-tracing-graphics] As a demonstration of the principles involved in ray tracing, consider how one would find the intersection between a ray and a sphere.
[src:graphics/ray-tracing-graphics] This is merely the math behind the line–sphere intersection and the subsequent determination of the color of the pixel being calculated.
[src:graphics/ray-tracing-graphics] There is, of course, far more to the general process of ray tracing, but this demonstrates an example of the algorithms used.
[src:graphics/ray-tracing-graphics] where t is its distance between $\mathbf {x}$ and $\mathbf {s}$ .
[src:graphics/ray-tracing-graphics] In our problem, we know $\mathbf {c}$ , r , $\mathbf {s}$ (e.g. the position of a light source) and $\mathbf {d}$ , and we need to find t .
[src:graphics/ray-tracing-graphics] The two values of t found by solving this equation are the two ones such that $\mathbf {s} +t\mathbf {d}$ are the points where the ray intersects the sphere.
[src:graphics/ray-tracing-graphics] Any value which is negative does not lie on the ray, but rather in the opposite half-line (i.e. the one starting from $\mathbf {s}$ with opposite direction).
[src:graphics/ray-tracing-graphics] If the quantity under the square root (the discriminant) is negative, then the ray does not intersect the sphere.
[src:graphics/ray-tracing-graphics] Let us suppose now that there is at least a positive solution, and let t be the minimal one.
[src:graphics/ray-tracing-graphics] In addition, let us suppose that the sphere is the nearest object on our scene intersecting our ray, and that it is made of a reflective material.
[src:graphics/ray-tracing-graphics] We need to find in which direction the light ray is reflected.
[src:graphics/ray-tracing-graphics] The laws of reflection state that the angle of reflection is equal and opposite to the angle of incidence between the incident ray and the normal to the sphere.
[src:graphics/ray-tracing-graphics] where $\mathbf {y} =\mathbf {s} +t\mathbf {d}$ is the intersection point found before.
[src:graphics/ray-tracing-graphics] Now we only need to compute the intersection of the latter ray with our field of view, to get the pixel which our reflected light ray will hit.
[src:graphics/ray-tracing-graphics] Lastly, this pixel is set to an appropriate color, taking into account how the color of the original light source and that of the sphere are combined by the reflection.
[src:graphics/ray-tracing-graphics] Adaptive depth control means that the renderer stops generating reflected/transmitted rays when the computed intensity becomes less than a certain threshold.
[src:graphics/ray-tracing-graphics] There must always be a set maximum depth or else the program would generate an infinite number of rays.
[src:graphics/ray-tracing-graphics] But it is not always necessary to go to the maximum depth if the surfaces are not highly reflective.
[src:graphics/ray-tracing-graphics] To test for this the ray tracer must compute and keep the product of the global and reflection coefficients as the rays are traced.
[src:graphics/ray-tracing-graphics] Example: let Kr = 0.5 for a set of surfaces.
[src:graphics/ray-tracing-graphics] In addition we might implement a distance attenuation factor such as 1/D2, which would also decrease the intensity contribution.
[src:graphics/ray-tracing-graphics] For a transmitted ray we could do something similar but in that case the distance traveled through the object would cause even faster intensity decrease.
[src:graphics/ray-tracing-graphics] As an example of this, Hall & Greenberg found that even for a very reflective scene, using this with a maximum depth of 15 resulted in an average ray tree depth of 1.7.
[src:graphics/ray-tracing-graphics] Enclosing groups of objects in sets of bounding volume hierarchies (BVH) decreases the amount of computations required for ray tracing.
[src:graphics/ray-tracing-graphics] A cast ray is first tested for an intersection with the bounding volume, and then if there is an intersection, the volume is recursively divided until the ray hits the object.
[src:graphics/ray-tracing-graphics] The best type of bounding volume will be determined by the shape of the underlying object or objects.
[src:graphics/ray-tracing-graphics] For example, if the objects are long and thin, then a sphere will enclose mainly empty space compared to a box.
[src:graphics/ray-tracing-graphics] Boxes are also easier to generate hierarchical bounding volumes.
[src:graphics/ray-tracing-graphics] Note that using a hierarchical system like this (assuming it is done carefully) changes the intersection computational time from a linear dependence on the number of objects to something between linear and a logarithmic dependence.
[src:graphics/ray-tracing-graphics] This is because, for a perfect case, each intersection test would divide the possibilities by two, and result in a binary tree type structure.
[src:graphics/ray-tracing-graphics] Spatial subdivision methods, discussed below, try to achieve this.
[src:graphics/ray-tracing-graphics] Furthermore, this acceleration structure makes the ray tracing computation output-sensitive.
[src:graphics/ray-tracing-graphics] I.e. the complexity of the ray intersection calculations depends on the number of objects that actually intersect the rays and not (only) on the number of objects in the scene.
[src:graphics/ray-tracing-graphics] The first implementation of an interactive ray tracer was the LINKS-1 Computer Graphics System built in 1982 at Osaka University's School of Engineering, by professors Ohmura Kouichi, Shirakawa Isao and Kawata Toru with 50 students.
[src:graphics/ray-tracing-graphics] It was a massively parallel processing computer system with 514 microprocessors (257 Zilog Z8001s and 257 iAPX 86s), used for 3D computer graphics with high-speed ray tracing.
[src:graphics/ray-tracing-graphics] According to the Information Processing Society of Japan: "The core of 3-D image rendering is calculating the luminance of each pixel making up a rendered surface from the given viewpoint, light source, and object position.
[src:graphics/ray-tracing-graphics] By developing a new software methodology specifically for high-speed image rendering, LINKS-1 was able to rapidly render highly realistic images." It was used to create an early 3-D planetarium-like video of the heavens made completely with computer graphics.
[src:graphics/ray-tracing-graphics] The video was presented at the Fujitsu pavilion at the 1985 International Exposition in Tsukuba." It was the second system to do so after the Evans & Sutherland Digistar in 1982.
[src:graphics/ray-tracing-graphics] The LINKS-1 was claimed by the designers to be the world's most powerful computer in 1984.
[src:graphics/ray-tracing-graphics] The next interactive ray tracer, and the first known to have been labeled "real-time" was credited at the 2005 SIGGRAPH computer graphics conference as being the REMRT/RT tools developed in 1986 by Mike Muuss for the BRL-CAD solid modeling system.
[src:graphics/ray-tracing-graphics] Initially published in 1987 at USENIX, the BRL-CAD ray tracer was an early implementation of a parallel network distributed ray tracing system that achieved several frames per second in rendering performance.
[src:graphics/ray-tracing-graphics] This performance was attained by means of the highly optimized yet platform independent LIBRT ray tracing engine in BRL-CAD and by using solid implicit CSG geometry on several shared memory parallel machines over a commodity network.
[src:graphics/ray-tracing-graphics] BRL-CAD's ray tracer, including the REMRT/RT tools, continue to be available and developed today as open source software.
[src:graphics/ray-tracing-graphics] Since then, there have been considerable efforts and research towards implementing ray tracing at real-time speeds for a variety of purposes on stand-alone desktop configurations.
[src:graphics/ray-tracing-graphics] These purposes include interactive 3-D graphics applications such as demoscene productions, computer and video games, and image rendering.
[src:graphics/ray-tracing-graphics] Some real-time software 3-D engines based on ray tracing have been developed by hobbyist demo programmers since the late 1990s.
[src:graphics/ray-tracing-graphics] In 1999 a team from the University of Utah, led by Steven Parker, demonstrated interactive ray tracing live at the 1999 Symposium on Interactive 3D Graphics.
[src:graphics/ray-tracing-graphics] They rendered a 35 million sphere model at 512 by 512 pixel resolution, running at approximately 15 frames per second on 60 CPUs.
[src:graphics/ray-tracing-graphics] The Open RT project included a highly optimized software core for ray tracing along with an OpenGL-like API in order to offer an alternative to the current rasterization based approach for interactive 3-D graphics.
[src:graphics/ray-tracing-graphics] Ray tracing hardware, such as the experimental Ray Processing Unit developed by Sven Woop at the Saarland University, was designed to accelerate some of the computationally intensive operations of ray tracing.
[src:graphics/ray-tracing-graphics] The idea that video games could ray trace their graphics in real time received media attention in the late 2000s.
[src:graphics/ray-tracing-graphics] Intel, a patron of Saarland, became impressed enough that it hired Pohl and embarked on a research program dedicated to ray traced graphics, which it saw as justifying increasing the number of its processors' cores.
[src:graphics/ray-tracing-graphics] On June 12, 2008, Intel demonstrated a special version of *Enemy Territory: Quake Wars*, titled *Quake Wars: Ray Traced*, using ray tracing for rendering, running in basic HD (720p) resolution.
[src:graphics/ray-tracing-graphics] *ETQW* operated at 14–29 frames per second on a 16-core (4 socket, 4 core) Xeon Tigerton system running at 2.93 GHz.
[src:graphics/ray-tracing-graphics] At SIGGRAPH 2009, Nvidia announced OptiX, a free API for real-time ray tracing on Nvidia GPUs.
[src:graphics/ray-tracing-graphics] The API exposes seven programmable entry points within the ray tracing pipeline, allowing for custom cameras, ray-primitive intersections, shaders, shadowing, etc.
[src:graphics/ray-tracing-graphics] This flexibility enables bidirectional path tracing, Metropolis light transport, and many other rendering algorithms that cannot be implemented with tail recursion.
[src:graphics/ray-tracing-graphics] OptiX-based renderers are used in Autodesk Arnold, Adobe AfterEffects, Bunkspeed Shot, Autodesk Maya, 3ds max, and many other renderers.
[src:graphics/ray-tracing-graphics] Nvidia introduced their GeForce RTX and Quadro RTX GPUs in September 2018, based on the Turing architecture that allows for hardware-accelerated ray tracing.
[src:graphics/ray-tracing-graphics] The Nvidia hardware uses a separate functional block, publicly called an "RT core".
[src:graphics/ray-tracing-graphics] This unit is somewhat comparable to a texture unit in size, latency, and interface to the processor core.
[src:graphics/ray-tracing-graphics] The unit features BVH traversal, compressed BVH node decompression, ray-AABB intersection testing, and ray-triangle intersection testing.
[src:graphics/ray-tracing-graphics] AMD, which already offered interactive ray tracing on top of OpenCL through its Radeon ProRender, unveiled in October 2020 the Radeon RX 6000 series, its second generation Navi GPUs with support for hardware-accelerated ray tracing at an online event.
[src:graphics/ray-tracing-graphics] Subsequent games that render their graphics by such means appeared since, which has been credited to the improvements in hardware and efforts to make more APIs and game engines compatible with the technology.
[src:graphics/ray-tracing-graphics] Current home gaming consoles implement dedicated ray tracing hardware in their GPUs for real-time ray tracing effects, which began with the ninth-generation consoles PlayStation 5, Xbox Series X and Series S.
[src:graphics/ray-tracing-graphics] On 4 November 2021, Imagination Technologies announced their IMG CXT GPU with hardware-accelerated ray tracing.
[src:graphics/ray-tracing-graphics] On January 18, 2022, Samsung announced their Exynos 2200 AP SoC with hardware-accelerated ray tracing.
[src:graphics/ray-tracing-graphics] On June 28, 2022, Arm announced their Immortalis-G715 with hardware-accelerated ray tracing.
[src:graphics/ray-tracing-graphics] On November 16, 2022, Qualcomm announced their Snapdragon 8 Gen 2 with hardware-accelerated ray tracing.
[src:graphics/ray-tracing-graphics] On September 12, 2023, Apple introduced hardware-accelerated ray tracing in its chip designs, beginning with the A17 Pro chip for iPhone 15 Pro models.
[src:graphics/ray-tracing-graphics] Later the same year, Apple released M3 family of processors with HW enabled ray tracing support.
[src:graphics/ray-tracing-graphics] Currently, this technology is accessible across iPhones, iPads, and Mac computers via the Metal API.
[src:graphics/ray-tracing-graphics] Apple reports up to a 4x performance increase over previous software-based ray tracing on the phone and up to 2.5x faster comparing M3 to M1 chips.
[src:graphics/ray-tracing-graphics] The hardware implementation includes acceleration structure traversal and dedicated ray-box intersections, and the API supports RayQuery (Inline Ray Tracing) as well as RayPipeline features.
[src:graphics/ray-tracing-graphics] Various complexity results have been proven for certain formulations of the ray tracing problem.
[src:graphics/rgb-color-model] The **RGB color model** is an additive color model in which the red, green, and blue primary colors of light are added together in various ways to reproduce a broad array of colors.
[src:graphics/rgb-color-model] The name of the model comes from the initials of the three additive primary colors— red, green, and blue.
[src:graphics/rgb-color-model] The main purpose of the RGB color model is for the sensing, representation, and display of images in electronic systems, such as televisions and computers, though it has also been used in conventional photography and colored lighting.
[src:graphics/rgb-color-model] Before the electronic age, the RGB color model already had a solid theory behind it, based in human perception of colors.
[src:graphics/rgb-color-model] Thus an RGB value does not define the same *color* across devices without some kind of color management.
[src:graphics/rgb-color-model] Typical RGB input devices are color TV and video cameras, image scanners, and digital cameras.
[src:graphics/rgb-color-model] Typical RGB output devices are TV sets of various technologies (CRT, LCD, plasma, OLED, quantum dots, etc.), computer and mobile phone displays, video projectors, multicolor LED displays and large screens such as the Jumbotron.
[src:graphics/rgb-color-model] Color printers, on the other hand, are not RGB devices, but subtractive color devices typically using the CMYK color model.
[src:graphics/rgb-color-model] To form a color with RGB, three light beams (one red, one green, and one blue) must be superimposed (for example by emission from a black screen or by reflection from a white screen).
[src:graphics/rgb-color-model] Each of the three beams is called a *component* of that color, and each of them can have an arbitrary intensity, from fully off to fully on, in the mixture.
[src:graphics/rgb-color-model] The RGB color model is *additive* in the sense that if light beams are superposed their emission spectra adds up, wavelength for wavelength, to make up a resulting, new emission spectrum.
[src:graphics/rgb-color-model] This is in contrast to the subtractive color model, particularly the CMY Color Model, which applies to paints, inks, dyes and other substances, in which, when two colors are combined, their reflection spectrum multiplies wavelength for wavelength.
[src:graphics/rgb-color-model] In the additive model, if the resulting spectrum, e.g. of superposing three colors, is flat, white color is perceived by the human eye upon direct incidence on the retina.
[src:graphics/rgb-color-model] This is in stark contrast to the subtractive model, where the perceived resulting spectrum is what reflecting surfaces, such as dyed surfaces, emit.
[src:graphics/rgb-color-model] There is no common color component among magenta, cyan and yellow, thus rendering a spectrum of zero intensity: black.
[src:graphics/rgb-color-model] When the intensities for all the components are the same, the result is a shade of gray, darker, or lighter depending on the intensity.
[src:graphics/rgb-color-model] When the intensities are different, the result is a colorized hue, more or less saturated depending on the difference of the strongest and weakest of the intensities of the primary colors employed.
[src:graphics/rgb-color-model] When one of the components has the strongest intensity, the color is a hue near this primary color (red-ish, green-ish, or blue-ish), and when two components have the same strongest intensity, then the color is a hue of a secondary color (a shade of cyan, magenta, or yellow).
[src:graphics/rgb-color-model] A secondary color is formed by the sum of two primary colors of equal intensity: cyan is green+blue, magenta is blue+red, and yellow is red+green.
[src:graphics/rgb-color-model] Every secondary color is the complement of one primary color: cyan complements red, magenta complements green, and yellow complements blue.
[src:graphics/rgb-color-model] When all the primary colors are mixed in equal intensities, the result is white.
[src:graphics/rgb-color-model] The RGB color model itself does not define what is meant by *red*, *green*, and *blue* colorimetrically, and so the results of mixing them are not specified as absolute, but relative to the primary colors.
[src:graphics/rgb-color-model] When the exact chromaticities of the red, green, and blue primaries are defined, the color model then becomes an absolute color space, such as sRGB or Adobe RGB.
[src:graphics/rgb-color-model] The choice of primary colors is related to the physiology of the human eye; good primaries are stimuli that maximize the difference between the responses of the cone cells of the human retina to light of different wavelengths, and that thereby make a large color triangle.
[src:graphics/rgb-color-model] The normal three kinds of light-sensitive photoreceptor cells in the human eye (cone cells) respond most to yellow (long wavelength or L), green (medium or M), and violet (short or S) light (peak wavelengths near 570 nm, 540 nm and 440 nm, respectively).
[src:graphics/rgb-color-model] The difference in the signals received from the three kinds allows the brain to differentiate a wide gamut of different colors, while being most sensitive (overall) to yellowish-green light and to differences between hues in the green-to-orange region.
[src:graphics/rgb-color-model] As an example, suppose that light in the orange range of wavelengths (approximately 577 nm to 597 nm) enters the eye and strikes the retina.
[src:graphics/rgb-color-model] Light of these wavelengths would activate both the medium and long wavelength cones of the retina, but not equally—the long-wavelength cells will respond more.
[src:graphics/rgb-color-model] The difference in the response can be detected by the brain, and this difference is the basis of our perception of orange.
[src:graphics/rgb-color-model] Thus, the orange appearance of an object results from light from the object entering our eye and stimulating the different cones simultaneously but to different degrees.
[src:graphics/rgb-color-model] Use of the three primary colors is not sufficient to reproduce *all* colors; only colors within the color triangle defined by the chromaticities of the primaries can be reproduced by additive mixing of non-negative amounts of those colors of light.
[src:graphics/rgb-color-model] The RGB color model is based on the Young–Helmholtz theory of trichromatic color vision, developed by Thomas Young and Hermann von Helmholtz in the early to mid-nineteenth century, and on James Clerk Maxwell's color triangle that elaborated that theory (c.
[src:graphics/rgb-color-model] The Young-Helmoltz theory found that red, green, and violet (instead of blue) make up all sensations of color.
[src:graphics/rgb-color-model] The first experiments with RGB in early color photography were made in 1861 by Maxwell himself, and involved the process of combining three color-filtered separate takes.
[src:graphics/rgb-color-model] To reproduce the color photograph, three matching projections over a screen in a dark room were necessary.
[src:graphics/rgb-color-model] The additive RGB model and variants such as orange–green–violet were also used in the Autochrome Lumière color plates and other screen-plate technologies such as the Joly color screen and the Paget process in the early twentieth century.
[src:graphics/rgb-color-model] Color photography by taking three separate plates was used by other pioneers, such as the Russian Sergey Prokudin-Gorsky in the period 1909 through 1915.
[src:graphics/rgb-color-model] Such methods lasted until about 1960 using the expensive and extremely complex tri-color carbro Autotype process.
[src:graphics/rgb-color-model] When employed, the reproduction of prints from three-plate photos was done by dyes or pigments using the complementary CMY model, by simply using the negative plates of the filtered takes: reverse red gives the cyan plate, and so on.
[src:graphics/rgb-color-model] Before the development of practical electronic TV, there were patents on mechanically scanned color systems as early as 1889 in Russia.
[src:graphics/rgb-color-model] The color TV pioneer John Logie Baird demonstrated the world's first RGB color transmission in 1928, and also the world's first color broadcast in 1938, in London.
[src:graphics/rgb-color-model] In his experiments, scanning and display were done mechanically by spinning colorized wheels.
[src:graphics/rgb-color-model] The Columbia Broadcasting System (CBS) began an experimental RGB field-sequential color system in 1940.
[src:graphics/rgb-color-model] Images were scanned electrically, but the system still used a moving part: the transparent RGB color wheel rotating at above 1,200 rpm in synchronism with the vertical scan.
[src:graphics/rgb-color-model] The camera and the cathode-ray tube (CRT) were both monochromatic.
[src:graphics/rgb-color-model] Color was provided by color wheels in the camera and the receiver.
[src:graphics/rgb-color-model] More recently, color wheels have been used in field-sequential projection TV receivers based on the Texas Instruments monochrome DLP imager.
[src:graphics/rgb-color-model] The modern RGB shadow mask technology for color CRT displays was patented by Werner Flechsig in Germany in 1938.
[src:graphics/rgb-color-model] Personal computers of the late 1970s and early 1980s, such as the Apple II and VIC-20, use composite video.
[src:graphics/rgb-color-model] The Commodore 64 and the Atari 8-bit computers use S-Video derivatives.
[src:graphics/rgb-color-model] IBM introduced a 16-color scheme (4 bit RGBI —1 bit each for red, green, blue, and intensity) with the Color Graphics Adapter (CGA) for its IBM PC in 1981, later improved with the Enhanced Graphics Adapter (EGA) in 1984.
[src:graphics/rgb-color-model] In 1992, magazines heavily advertised true-color Super VGA hardware.
[src:graphics/rgb-color-model] One common application of the RGB color model is the display of colors on a cathode-ray tube (CRT), liquid-crystal display (LCD), plasma display, or organic light emitting diode (OLED) display such as a television, a computer's monitor, or a large scale screen.
[src:graphics/rgb-color-model] Each pixel on the screen is built by driving three small and very close but still separated RGB light sources.
[src:graphics/rgb-color-model] At common viewing distance, the separate sources are indistinguishable, which the eye interprets as a given solid color.
[src:graphics/rgb-color-model] All the pixels together arranged in the rectangular screen surface conforms the color image.
[src:graphics/rgb-color-model] During digital image processing each pixel can be represented in the computer memory or interface hardware (for example, a *graphics card*) as binary values for the red, green, and blue color components.
[src:graphics/rgb-color-model] When properly managed, these values are converted into intensities or voltages via gamma correction to correct the inherent nonlinearity of some devices, such that the intended intensities are reproduced on the display.
[src:graphics/rgb-color-model] The Quattron released by Sharp uses RGB color and adds yellow as a sub-pixel, supposedly allowing an increase in the number of available colors.
[src:graphics/rgb-color-model] RGB is also the term referring to a type of component video signal used in the video electronics industry.
[src:graphics/rgb-color-model] It consists of three signals—red, green, and blue—carried on three separate cables/pins.
[src:graphics/rgb-color-model] RGB signal formats are often based on modified versions of the RS-170 and RS-343 standards for monochrome video.
[src:graphics/rgb-color-model] This type of video signal is widely used in Europe since it is the best quality signal that can be carried on the standard SCART connector.
[src:graphics/rgb-color-model] This signal is known as RGBS (4 BNC/RCA terminated cables exist as well), but it is directly compatible with RGBHV used for computer monitors (usually carried on 15-pin cables terminated with 15-pin D-sub or 5 BNC connectors), which carries separate horizontal and vertical sync signals.
[src:graphics/rgb-color-model] Outside Europe, RGB is not very popular as a video signal format; S-Video takes that spot in most non-European regions.
[src:graphics/rgb-color-model] However, almost all computer monitors around the world use RGB.
[src:graphics/rgb-color-model] The synchronization signal is necessary to establish the timing for displaying the color sample on the screen, governing both the horizontal direction (the progression of the image line) and the vertical direction (the jump to a new image line).
[src:graphics/rgb-color-model] Composite synchronization (RGBS): With this method, there is a single signal containing all horizontal and vertical synchronization information, independent of the color signals, resulting in a total of four signals in the transmission.
[src:graphics/rgb-color-model] Sync on Green (RGsB or SoG): With this method, there is a single signal containing all horizontal and vertical synchronization information multiplexed with the green color signal, resulting in a total of three signals in the transmission.
[src:graphics/rgb-color-model] Note that this model applies only to screens and light-based displays.
[src:graphics/rgb-color-model] It does not apply to pigments (paint), which follow the subtractive color model.
[src:graphics/rgb-color-model] A framebuffer is a digital device for computers which stores data in the so-called *video memory* (comprising an array of Video RAM or similar chips).
[src:graphics/rgb-color-model] This data goes either to three digital-to-analog converters (DACs) (for analog monitors), one per primary color or directly to digital monitors.
[src:graphics/rgb-color-model] Driven by software, the CPU (or other specialized chips) write the appropriate bytes into the video memory to define the image.
[src:graphics/rgb-color-model] Modern systems encode pixel color values by devoting 8 bits to each of the R, G, and B components.
[src:graphics/rgb-color-model] RGB information can be either carried directly by the pixel bits themselves or provided by a separate **color look-up table** (**CLUT**) if indexed color graphic modes are used.
[src:graphics/rgb-color-model] A CLUT is a specialized RAM that stores R, G, and B values that define specific colors.
[src:graphics/rgb-color-model] Each color has its own address (index)—consider it as a descriptive reference number that provides that specific color when the image needs it.
[src:graphics/rgb-color-model] The content of the CLUT is much like a palette of colors.
[src:graphics/rgb-color-model] Image data that uses indexed color specifies addresses within the CLUT to provide the required R, G, and B values for each specific pixel, one pixel at a time.
[src:graphics/rgb-color-model] Of course, before displaying, the CLUT has to be loaded with R, G, and B values that define the palette of colors required for each image to be rendered.
[src:graphics/rgb-color-model] Some video applications store such palettes in PAL files (*Age of Empires* game, for example, uses over half-a-dozen) and can combine CLUTs on screen.
[src:graphics/rgb-color-model] However, the advantage is that an indexed-color image file can be significantly smaller than it would be with only 8 bits per pixel for each primary.
[src:graphics/rgb-color-model] Modern storage, however, is far less costly, greatly reducing the need to minimize image file size.
[src:graphics/rgb-color-model] By using an appropriate combination of red, green, and blue intensities, many colors can be displayed.
[src:graphics/rgb-color-model] Current typical display adapters use up to 24 bits of information for each pixel: 8-bit per component multiplied by three components (see the Numeric representations section below (24 bits = 2563, each primary value of 8 bits with values of 0–255).
[src:graphics/rgb-color-model] With this system, 16,777,216 (2563 or 224) discrete combinations of R, G, and B values are allowed, providing millions of different (though not necessarily distinguishable) hue, saturation and lightness shades.
[src:graphics/rgb-color-model] Increased shading has been implemented in various ways, some formats such as .png and .tga files among others using a fourth grayscale color channel as a masking layer, often called **RGB32**.
[src:graphics/rgb-color-model] For images with a modest range of brightnesses from the darkest to the lightest, 8 bits per primary color provides good-quality images, but extreme images require more bits per primary color as well as the advanced display technology.
[src:graphics/rgb-color-model] For more information see High Dynamic Range (HDR) imaging.
[src:graphics/rgb-color-model] In classic CRT devices, the brightness of a given point over the fluorescent screen due to the impact of accelerated electrons is not proportional to the voltages applied to the electron gun control grids, but to an expansive function of that voltage.
[src:graphics/rgb-color-model] The amount of this deviation is known as its gamma value ( $\gamma$ ), the argument for a power law function, which closely describes this behavior.
[src:graphics/rgb-color-model] A linear response is given by a gamma value of 1.0, but actual CRT nonlinearities have a gamma value around 2.0 to 2.5.
[src:graphics/rgb-color-model] Similarly, the intensity of the output on TV and computer display devices is not directly proportional to the R, G, and B applied electric signals (or file data values which drive them through digital-to-analog converters).
[src:graphics/rgb-color-model] On a typical standard 2.2-gamma CRT display, an input intensity RGB value of (0.5, 0.5, 0.5) only outputs about 22% of full brightness (1.0, 1.0, 1.0), instead of 50%.
[src:graphics/rgb-color-model] To obtain the correct response, a gamma correction is used in encoding the image data, and possibly further corrections as part of the color calibration process of the device.
[src:graphics/rgb-color-model] Gamma affects black-and-white TV as well as color.
[src:graphics/rgb-color-model] In standard color TV, broadcast signals are gamma corrected.
[src:graphics/rgb-color-model] In color television and video cameras manufactured before the 1990s, the incoming light was separated by prisms and filters into the three RGB primary colors feeding each color into a separate video camera tube (or *pickup tube*).
[src:graphics/rgb-color-model] These tubes are a type of cathode-ray tube, not to be confused with that of CRT displays.
[src:graphics/rgb-color-model] With the arrival of commercially viable charge-coupled device (CCD) technology in the 1980s, first, the pickup tubes were replaced with this kind of sensor.
[src:graphics/rgb-color-model] Later, higher scale integration electronics was applied (mainly by Sony), simplifying and even removing the intermediate optics, thereby reducing the size of home video cameras and eventually leading to the development of full camcorders.
[src:graphics/rgb-color-model] Current webcams and mobile phones with cameras are the most miniaturized commercial forms of such technology.
[src:graphics/rgb-color-model] Photographic digital cameras that use a CMOS or CCD image sensor often operate with some variation of the RGB model.
[src:graphics/rgb-color-model] In a Bayer filter arrangement, green is given twice as many detectors as red and blue (ratio 1:2:1) in order to achieve higher luminance resolution than chrominance resolution.
[src:graphics/rgb-color-model] The sensor has a grid of red, green, and blue detectors arranged so that the first row is RGRGRGRG, the next is GBGBGBGB, and that sequence is repeated in subsequent rows.
[src:graphics/rgb-color-model] For every channel, missing pixels are obtained by interpolation in the demosaicing process to build up the complete image.
[src:graphics/rgb-color-model] Also, other processes used to be applied in order to map the camera RGB measurements into a standard color space as sRGB.
[src:graphics/rgb-color-model] In computing, an image scanner is a device that optically scans images (printed text, handwriting, or an object) and converts it to a digital image which is transferred to a computer.
[src:graphics/rgb-color-model] Among other formats, flat, drum and film scanners exist, and most of them support RGB color.
[src:graphics/rgb-color-model] They can be considered the successors of early telephotography input devices, which were able to send consecutive scan lines as analog amplitude modulation signals through standard telephonic lines to appropriate receivers; such systems were in use in press since the 1920s to the mid-1990s.
[src:graphics/rgb-color-model] Color telephotographs were sent as three separated RGB filtered images consecutively.
[src:graphics/rgb-color-model] Currently available scanners typically use CCD or contact image sensor (CIS) as the image sensor, whereas older drum scanners use a photomultiplier tube as the image sensor.
[src:graphics/rgb-color-model] Early color film scanners used a halogen lamp and a three-color filter wheel, so three exposures were needed to scan a single color image.
[src:graphics/rgb-color-model] Due to heating problems, the worst of them being the potential destruction of the scanned film, this technology was later replaced by non-heating light sources such as color LEDs.
[src:graphics/rgb-color-model] A color in the RGB color model is described by indicating how much of each of the red, green, and blue is included.
[src:graphics/rgb-color-model] The color is expressed as an RGB triplet (*r*,*g*,*b*), each component of which can vary from zero to a defined maximum value.
[src:graphics/rgb-color-model] If all the components are at zero the result is black; if all are at maximum, the result is the brightest representable white.
[src:graphics/rgb-color-model] In many environments, the component values within the ranges are not managed as linear (that is, the numbers are nonlinearly related to the intensities that they represent), as in digital cameras and TV broadcasting and receiving due to gamma correction, for example.
[src:graphics/rgb-color-model] Linear and nonlinear transformations are often dealt with via digital image processing.
[src:graphics/rgb-color-model] Representations with only 8 bits per component are considered sufficient if gamma correction is used.
[src:graphics/rgb-color-model] The RGB color model is one of the most common ways to encode color in computing, and several different digital representations are in use.
[src:graphics/rgb-color-model] The main characteristic of all of them is the quantization of the possible values per component (technically a *sample*) by using only integer numbers within some range, usually from 0 to some power of two minus one (2*n* − 1) to fit them into some bit groupings.
[src:graphics/rgb-color-model] Encodings of 1, 2, 4, 5, 8, and 16 bits per color are commonly found; the total number of bits used for an RGB color is typically called the color depth.
[src:graphics/rgb-color-model] Since colors are usually defined by three components, not only in the RGB model, but also in other color models such as CIELAB and Y'UV, among others, then a three-dimensional volume is described by treating the component values as ordinary Cartesian coordinates in a Euclidean space.
[src:graphics/rgb-color-model] For the RGB model, this is represented by a cube using non-negative values within a 0–1 range, assigning black to the origin at the vertex (0, 0, 0), and with increasing intensity values running along the three axes up to white at the vertex (1, 1, 1), diagonally opposite black.
[src:graphics/rgb-color-model] An RGB triplet (*r*,*g*,*b*) represents the three-dimensional coordinate of the point of the given color within the cube or its faces or along its edges.
[src:graphics/rgb-color-model] This approach allows computations of the color similarity of two given RGB colors by simply calculating the distance between them: the shorter the distance, the higher the similarity.
[src:graphics/rgb-color-model] Out-of-gamut computations can also be performed this way.
[src:graphics/rgb-color-model] Initially, the limited color depth of most video hardware led to a limited color palette of 216 RGB colors, defined by the Netscape Color Cube.
[src:graphics/rgb-color-model] The web-safe color palette consists of the 216 (63) combinations of red, green, and blue where each color can take one of six values (in hexadecimal): #00, #33, #66, #99, #CC or #FF (based on the 0 to 255 range for each value discussed above).
[src:graphics/rgb-color-model] This seems fine for splitting up 216 colors into a cube of dimension 6.
[src:graphics/rgb-color-model] However, lacking gamma correction, the perceived intensity on a standard 2.5 gamma CRT / LCD is only: 0%, 2%, 10%, 28%, 57%, 100%.
[src:graphics/rgb-color-model] See the actual web safe color palette for a visual confirmation that the majority of the colors produced are very dark.
[src:graphics/rgb-color-model] With the predominance of 24-bit displays, the use of the full 16.7 million colors of the HTML RGB color code no longer poses problems for most viewers.
[src:graphics/rgb-color-model] The sRGB color space (a *device-independent* color space) for HTML was formally adopted as an Internet standard in HTML 3.2, though it had been in use for some time before that.
[src:graphics/rgb-color-model] All images and colors are interpreted as being sRGB (unless another color space is specified) and all modern displays can display this color space (with color management being built in into browsers or operating systems).
[src:graphics/rgb-color-model] where # equals the proportion of red, green, and blue respectively.
[src:graphics/rgb-color-model] This syntax can be used after such selectors as "background-color:" or (for text) "color:".
[src:graphics/rgb-color-model] Wide gamut color is possible in modern CSS, being supported by all major browsers since 2023.
[src:graphics/rgb-color-model] where # equals the proportion of red, green, and blue in 0.0 to 1.0 respectively.
[src:graphics/rgb-color-model] Proper reproduction of colors, especially in professional environments, requires color management of all the devices involved in the production process, many of them using RGB.
[src:graphics/rgb-color-model] Color management results in several transparent conversions between device-independent (sRGB, XYZ, L*a*b*) and device-dependent color spaces (RGB and others, as CMYK for color printing) during a typical production cycle, in order to ensure color consistency throughout the process.
[src:graphics/rgb-color-model] Along with the creative processing, such interventions on digital images can damage the color accuracy and image detail, especially where the gamut is reduced.
[src:graphics/rgb-color-model] Professional digital devices and software tools allow for 48 bpp (bits per pixel) images to be manipulated (16 bits per channel), to minimize any such damage.
[src:graphics/rgb-color-model] ICC profile compliant applications, such as Adobe Photoshop, use either the Lab color space or the CIE 1931 color space as a *Profile Connection Space* when translating between color spaces.
[src:graphics/rgb-color-model] These intermediate formats were needed for compatibility with pre-existent black-and-white TV formats.
[src:graphics/rgb-color-model] Also, those color difference signals need lower data bandwidth compared to full RGB signals.
[src:graphics/rgb-color-model] Similarly, current high-efficiency digital color image data compression schemes such as JPEG and MPEG store RGB color internally in YCBCR format, a digital luminance–chrominance format based on YPBPR.
[src:graphics/rgb-color-model] The use of YCBCR also allows computers to perform lossy subsampling with the chrominance channels (typically to 4:2:2 or 4:1:1 ratios), which reduces the resultant file size.
[src:graphics/shader] In computer graphics, a **shader** is a programmable operation which is applied to data as it moves through the rendering pipeline.
[src:graphics/shader] Shaders act on data such as vertices and primitives, generate or morph geometries and fragments, and calculate the colors in a rendered image.
[src:graphics/shader] Shaders can execute a wide variety of operations.
[src:graphics/shader] In modern real-time computer graphics, shaders are run on graphics processing units (GPUs) - dedicated hardware which provide parallel execution of programs.
[src:graphics/shader] Because image rendering is an embarrassingly parallel problem (having an Amdahl's index of one), shaders benefit greatly from parallel computing, such as SIMD hardware.
[src:graphics/shader] The drive for faster rendering has produced highly parallel processors, like GPUs, which are now used for general-purpose computing.
[src:graphics/shader] Shaders used for general purposes are commonly called *compute shaders*.
[src:graphics/shader] The term "shader" was first introduced to the public by Pixar with version 3.0 of their RenderMan Interface Specification, originally published in May 1988.
[src:graphics/shader] As graphics processing units evolved, major graphics software libraries such as OpenGL and Direct3D began to support shaders.
[src:graphics/shader] The first shader-capable GPUs only supported pixel shading, but vertex shaders were quickly introduced once developers realized the power of shaders.
[src:graphics/shader] The first video card with a programmable pixel shader was the Nvidia GeForce 3 (NV20), released in 2001.
[src:graphics/shader] Geometry shaders were introduced with Direct3D 10 and OpenGL 3.2.
[src:graphics/shader] Graphics hardware evolved toward a unified shader model, making all shaders equal.
[src:graphics/shader] The traditional use of shaders is to operate on data in the graphics pipeline to control the rendering of an image.
[src:graphics/shader] Graphics shaders are classified according to their position in the pipeline, the data being manipulated, and the graphics API being used.
[src:graphics/shader] Vertex shaders are run once for each 3D vertex given to the graphics processor.
[src:graphics/shader] The purpose is to transform each vertex's 3D position in virtual space to the 2D coordinate at which it appears on the screen (as well as a depth value for the Z-buffer).
[src:graphics/shader] Vertex shaders can manipulate properties such as position, color and texture coordinates, but cannot create new vertices.
[src:graphics/shader] The output of the vertex shader goes to the next stage in the pipeline, which is either a geometry shader if present, or the rasterizer.
[src:graphics/shader] Vertex shaders can enable powerful control over the details of position, movement, lighting, and color in any scene involving 3D models.
[src:graphics/shader] Geometry shaders were introduced in Direct3D 10 and OpenGL 3.2; formerly available in OpenGL 2.0+ with the use of extensions.
[src:graphics/shader] This type of shader can generate new graphics primitives, such as points, lines, and triangles, from those primitives that were sent to the beginning of the graphics pipeline.
[src:graphics/shader] Geometry shader programs are executed after vertex shaders.
[src:graphics/shader] They take as input a whole primitive, possibly with adjacency information.
[src:graphics/shader] For example, when operating on triangles, the three vertices are the geometry shader's input.
[src:graphics/shader] The shader can then emit zero or more primitives, which are rasterized and their fragments ultimately passed to a pixel shader.
[src:graphics/shader] Typical uses of a geometry shader include point sprite generation, geometry tessellation, shadow volume extrusion, and single pass rendering to a cube map.
[src:graphics/shader] A typical real-world example of the benefits of geometry shaders would be automatic mesh complexity modification.
[src:graphics/shader] A series of line strips representing control points for a curve are passed to the geometry shader and depending on the complexity required the shader can automatically generate extra lines each of which provides a better approximation of a curve.
[src:graphics/shader] model rendered using fragment shaders with different outputs: solid white, applied texture, physically based shading.
[src:graphics/shader] Fragment shaders, also known as **pixel shaders**, compute color and other attributes of each "fragment": a unit of rendering work affecting at most a single output pixel.
[src:graphics/shader] The simplest kinds of pixel shaders output one screen pixel as a color value; more complex shaders with multiple inputs/outputs are also possible.
[src:graphics/shader] Pixel shaders range from simply always outputting the same color, to applying a lighting value, to doing bump mapping, shadows, specular highlights, translucency and other phenomena.
[src:graphics/shader] They can alter the depth of the fragment (for Z-buffering), or output more than one color if multiple render targets are active.
[src:graphics/shader] In 3D graphics, a pixel shader alone cannot produce some kinds of complex effects because it operates only on a single fragment, without knowledge of a scene's geometry (i.e. vertex data).
[src:graphics/shader] However, pixel shaders do have knowledge of the screen coordinate being drawn, and can sample the screen and nearby pixels if the contents of the entire screen are passed as a texture to the shader.
[src:graphics/shader] This technique can enable a wide variety of two-dimensional postprocessing effects such as blur, or edge detection/enhancement for cartoon/cel shaders.
[src:graphics/shader] Pixel shaders may also be applied in *intermediate* stages to any two-dimensional images—sprites or textures—in the pipeline, whereas vertex shaders always require a 3D scene.
[src:graphics/shader] For instance, a pixel shader is the only kind of shader that can act as a postprocessor or filter for a video stream after it has been rasterized.
[src:graphics/shader] OpenGL 4.0 and Direct3D 11 introduced a new shader class called a tessellation shader.
[src:graphics/shader] The function can be related to a variety of variables, most notably the distance from the viewing camera to allow active level-of-detail scaling.
[src:graphics/shader] This allows objects close to the camera to have fine detail, while further away ones can have more coarse meshes, yet seem comparable in quality.
[src:graphics/shader] It also can drastically reduce required mesh bandwidth by allowing meshes to be refined once inside the shader units instead of down-sampling very complex ones from memory.
[src:graphics/shader] Some algorithms can up-sample any arbitrary mesh, while others allow for "hinting" in meshes to dictate the most characteristic vertices and edges.
[src:graphics/shader] Circa 2017, the AMD Vega microarchitecture added support for a new shader stage—primitive shaders—somewhat akin to compute shaders with access to the data necessary to process geometry.
[src:graphics/shader] Nvidia introduced mesh and task shaders with its Turing microarchitecture in 2018 which are also modelled after compute shaders.
[src:graphics/shader] Nvidia Turing is the world's first GPU microarchitecture that supports mesh shading through DirectX 12 Ultimate API, several months before Ampere RTX 30 series was released.
[src:graphics/shader] In 2020, AMD and Nvidia released RDNA 2 and Ampere microarchitectures which both support mesh shading through DirectX 12 Ultimate.
[src:graphics/shader] These mesh shaders allow the GPU to handle more complex algorithms, offloading more work from the CPU to the GPU, and in algorithm intense rendering, increasing the frame rate of or number of triangles in a scene by an order of magnitude.
[src:graphics/shader] Intel announced that Intel Arc Alchemist GPUs shipping in Q1 2022 will support mesh shaders.
[src:graphics/shader] Ray tracing shaders are supported by Microsoft via DirectX Raytracing, by Khronos Group via Vulkan, GLSL, and SPIR-V, by Apple via Metal.
[src:graphics/shader] Nvidia and AMD called the parts of the hardware responsible for executing these shaders "ray tracing cores".
[src:graphics/shader] Compute kernels are routines compiled for high throughput accelerators (such as graphics processing units (GPUs), digital signal processors (DSPs), or field-programmable gate arrays (FPGAs)), separate from but used by a main program (typically running on a central processing unit).
[src:graphics/shader] They may be specified by a separate programming language such as "OpenCL C", as "compute shaders" written in a shading language, or embedded directly in application code written in a high level language.
[src:graphics/shader] Compute kernels roughly correspond to inner loops when implementing algorithms in traditional languages (except there is no implied sequential operation), or to code passed to internal iterators.
[src:graphics/shader] Microsoft support this as DirectCompute.
[src:graphics/shader] This single program, multiple data programming paradigm maps well to vector processors: there is an assumption that each invocation of a kernel within a batch is independent, allowing for data parallel execution.
[src:graphics/shader] However, atomic operations may sometimes be used for synchronization between elements (for interdependent work), in some scenarios.
[src:graphics/shader] Individual invocations are given indices (in 1 or more dimensions) from which arbitrary addressing of buffer data may be performed (including scatter gather operations), so long as the non-overlapping assumption is respected.
[src:graphics/shader] The Vulkan API provides the intermediate SPIR-V representation to describe *both* graphical shaders, and compute kernels in a language independent and machine independent manner.
[src:graphics/shader] The intention is to facilitate language evolution and provide a more natural ability to leverage GPU compute capabilities, in line with hardware developments such as Unified Memory Architecture and Heterogeneous System Architecture.
[src:graphics/shader] This allows closer cooperation between a CPU and GPU.
[src:graphics/shader] Much work has been done in the field of Kernel generation through LLMs as a means of optimizing code.
[src:graphics/shader] KernelBench, created by the Scaling Intelligence Lab at Stanford, provides a framework to evaluate the ability of LLMs to generate efficient GPU kernels.
[src:graphics/shader] Cognition has created Kevin 32-B to create efficient CUDA kernels which is currently the highest performing model on KernelBench.
[src:graphics/shader] Tensor shaders are accelerator programs that deal with matrix operations on large arrays, a type of operation commonly used in neural network-based AI.
[src:graphics/shader] Tensor shaders are supported by Microsoft via DirectML, by Khronos Group via OpenVX, by Apple via Core ML, by Google via TensorFlow, by Linux Foundation via ONNX.
[src:graphics/shader] Nvidia and AMD called the parts of the hardware responsible for executing these shaders "tensor cores".
[src:graphics/shader] Several programming languages exist specifically for writing shaders, and which is used can depend on the target environment.
[src:graphics/shader] The shading language for OpenGL is GLSL, and Direct3D uses HLSL.
[src:graphics/shader] The Metal framework, used by Apple devices, has its own shading language called Metal Shading Language.
[src:graphics/shader] Increasingly in modern graphics APIs, shaders are compiled into SPIR-V, an intermediate language, before they are distributed to the end user.
[src:graphics/shader] This standard allows more flexible choice of shading language, regardless of target platform.
[src:graphics/shader] First supported by Vulkan and OpenGL, SPIR-V is also being adopted by Direct3D.
[src:graphics/shader] The graph is then compiled into a shader.
[src:graphics/shader] In web development contexts, visual and component-based shader tools have also emerged.
[src:graphics/shader] Platforms such as shaders.com provide component-driven composition of shaders for integration into frontend frameworks including Vue, React, and Svelte, while tools such as Shadertoy and FragCoord.xyz focus on lower-level shader authoring and debugging.
[src:graphics/spatial-anti-aliasing] In digital signal processing, **spatial anti-aliasing** is a technique for minimizing the distortion artifacts (aliasing) when representing a high-resolution image at a lower resolution.
[src:graphics/spatial-anti-aliasing] Anti-aliasing is used in digital photography, computer graphics, digital audio, and many other applications.
[src:graphics/spatial-anti-aliasing] Anti-aliasing means removing signal components that have a higher frequency than is able to be properly resolved by the recording (or sampling) device.
[src:graphics/spatial-anti-aliasing] This removal is done before (re)sampling at a lower resolution.
[src:graphics/spatial-anti-aliasing] When sampling is performed without removing this part of the signal, it causes undesirable artifacts such as black-and-white noise.
[src:graphics/spatial-anti-aliasing] In signal acquisition and audio, anti-aliasing is often done using an analog anti-aliasing filter to remove the out-of-band component of the input signal prior to sampling with an analog-to-digital converter.
[src:graphics/spatial-anti-aliasing] In digital photography, optical anti-aliasing filters made of birefringent materials smooth the signal in the spatial optical domain.
[src:graphics/spatial-anti-aliasing] The anti-aliasing filter essentially blurs the image slightly in order to reduce the resolution to or below that achievable by the digital sensor (the larger the pixel pitch, the lower the achievable resolution at the sensor level).
[src:graphics/spatial-anti-aliasing] In computer graphics, anti-aliasing improves the appearance of "jagged" polygon edges, or "jaggies", so they are smoothed out on the screen.
[src:graphics/spatial-anti-aliasing] However, it incurs a performance cost for the graphics card and uses more video memory.
[src:graphics/spatial-anti-aliasing] The level of anti-aliasing determines how smooth polygon edges are (and how much video memory it consumes).
[src:graphics/spatial-anti-aliasing] Near the top of an image with a receding checker-board pattern, the image is difficult to recognise and often not considered aesthetically pleasing.
[src:graphics/spatial-anti-aliasing] In contrast, when anti-aliased the checker-board near the top blends into grey, which is usually the desired effect when the resolution is insufficient to show the detail.
[src:graphics/spatial-anti-aliasing] Even near the bottom of the image, the edges appear much smoother in the anti-aliased image.
[src:graphics/spatial-anti-aliasing] Multiple methods exist, including the sinc filter, which is considered a better anti-aliasing algorithm.
[src:graphics/spatial-anti-aliasing] When magnified, it can be seen how anti-aliasing interpolates the brightness of the pixels at the boundaries to produce grey pixels since the space is occupied by both black and white tiles.
[src:graphics/spatial-anti-aliasing] These help make the sinc filter antialiased image appear much smoother than the original.
[src:graphics/spatial-anti-aliasing] In a simple diamond image, anti-aliasing blends the boundary pixels; this reduces the aesthetically jarring effect of the sharp, step-like boundaries that appear in the aliased graphic.
[src:graphics/spatial-anti-aliasing] Anti-aliasing is often applied in rendering text on a computer screen, to suggest smooth contours that better emulate the appearance of text produced by conventional ink-and-paper printing.
[src:graphics/spatial-anti-aliasing] Particularly with fonts displayed on typical LCD screens, it is common to use subpixel rendering techniques like ClearType.
[src:graphics/spatial-anti-aliasing] Sub-pixel rendering requires special colour-balanced anti-aliasing filters to turn what would be severe colour distortion into barely-noticeable colour fringes.
[src:graphics/spatial-anti-aliasing] Equivalent results can be had by making individual sub-pixels addressable as if they were full pixels, and supplying a hardware-based anti-aliasing filter as is done in the OLPC XO-1 laptop's display controller.
[src:graphics/spatial-anti-aliasing] Pixel geometry affects all of this, whether the anti-aliasing and sub-pixel addressing are done in software or hardware.
[src:graphics/spatial-anti-aliasing] The most basic approach to anti-aliasing a pixel is determining what percentage of the pixel is occupied by a given region in the vector graphic - in this case a pixel-sized square, possibly transposed over several pixels - and using that percentage as the colour.
[src:graphics/spatial-anti-aliasing] This method is generally best suited for simple graphics, such as basic lines or curves, and applications that would otherwise have to convert absolute coordinates to pixel-constrained coordinates, such as 3D graphics.
[src:graphics/spatial-anti-aliasing] It is a fairly fast function, but it is relatively low-quality, and gets slower as the complexity of the shape increases.
[src:graphics/spatial-anti-aliasing] For purposes requiring very high-quality graphics or very complex vector shapes, this will probably not be the best approach.
[src:graphics/spatial-anti-aliasing] Note: The `plot_antialiased_point` routine above cannot blindly set the colour value to the percent calculated.
[src:graphics/spatial-anti-aliasing] It must **add** the new value to the existing value at that location up to a maximum of 1.
[src:graphics/spatial-anti-aliasing] Otherwise, the brightness of each pixel will be equal to the darkest value calculated in time for that location which produces a very bad result.
[src:graphics/spatial-anti-aliasing] For example, if one point sets a brightness level of 0.90 for a given pixel and another point calculated later barely touches that pixel and has a brightness of 0.05, the final value set for that pixel should be 0.95, not 0.05.
[src:graphics/spatial-anti-aliasing] In this approach, the ideal image is regarded as a *signal*.
[src:graphics/spatial-anti-aliasing] The image displayed on the screen is taken as samples, at each (*x,y*) pixel position, of a filtered version of the signal.
[src:graphics/spatial-anti-aliasing] Ideally, one would understand how the human brain would process the original signal, and provide an on-screen image that will yield the most similar response by the brain.
[src:graphics/spatial-anti-aliasing] The most widely accepted analytic tool for such problems is the Fourier transform; this decomposes a signal into basis functions of different frequencies, known as frequency components, and gives us the amplitude of each frequency component in the signal.
[src:graphics/spatial-anti-aliasing] where *j* and *k* are arbitrary non-negative integers.
[src:graphics/spatial-anti-aliasing] There are also frequency components involving the sine functions in one or both dimensions, but for the purpose of this discussion, the cosine will suffice.
[src:graphics/spatial-anti-aliasing] The numbers *j* and *k* together are the *frequency* of the component: *j* is the frequency in the *x* direction, and *k* is the frequency in the *y* direction.
[src:graphics/spatial-anti-aliasing] Current knowledge of human visual perception is not sufficient, in general, to say what approach will look best.
[src:graphics/spatial-anti-aliasing] The previous discussion assumes that the rectangular mesh sampling is the dominant part of the problem.
[src:graphics/spatial-anti-aliasing] The filter usually considered optimal is not rotationally symmetrical, as shown in this first figure; this is because the data is sampled on a square lattice, not using a continuous image.
[src:graphics/spatial-anti-aliasing] This sampling pattern is the justification for doing signal processing along each axis, as it is traditionally done on one dimensional data.
[src:graphics/spatial-anti-aliasing] Lanczos resampling is based on convolution of the data with a discrete representation of the sinc function.
[src:graphics/spatial-anti-aliasing] If the resolution is not limited by the rectangular sampling rate of either the source or target image, then one should ideally use rotationally symmetrical filter or interpolation functions, as though the data were a two dimensional function of continuous x and y.
[src:graphics/spatial-anti-aliasing] The sinc function of the radius has too long a tail to make a good filter (it is not even square-integrable).
[src:graphics/spatial-anti-aliasing] A more appropriate analog to the one-dimensional sinc is the two-dimensional Airy disc amplitude, the 2D Fourier transform of a circular region in 2D frequency space, as opposed to a square region.
[src:graphics/spatial-anti-aliasing] One might consider a Gaussian plus enough of its second derivative to flatten the top (in the frequency domain) or sharpen it up (in the spatial domain), as shown.
[src:graphics/spatial-anti-aliasing] Functions based on the Gaussian function are natural choices, because convolution with a Gaussian gives another Gaussian whether applied to x and y or to the radius.
[src:graphics/spatial-anti-aliasing] Similarly to wavelets, another of its properties is that it is halfway between being localized in the configuration (x and y) and in the spectral (j and k) representation.
[src:graphics/spatial-anti-aliasing] As an interpolation function, a Gaussian alone seems too spread out to preserve the maximum possible detail, and thus the second derivative is added.
[src:graphics/spatial-anti-aliasing] As an example, when printing a photographic negative with plentiful processing capability and on a printer with a hexagonal pattern, there is no reason to use sinc function interpolation.
[src:graphics/spatial-anti-aliasing] Such interpolation would treat diagonal lines differently from horizontal and vertical lines, which is like a weak form of aliasing.
[src:graphics/spatial-anti-aliasing] There are only a handful of primitives used at the lowest level in a real-time rendering engine (either software or hardware accelerated).
[src:graphics/spatial-anti-aliasing] These include "points", "lines" and "triangles".
[src:graphics/spatial-anti-aliasing] If one is to draw such a primitive in white against a black background, it is possible to design such a primitive to have fuzzy edges, achieving some sort of anti-aliasing.
[src:graphics/spatial-anti-aliasing] However, this approach has difficulty dealing with adjacent primitives (such as triangles that share an edge).
[src:graphics/spatial-anti-aliasing] To approximate the uniform averaging algorithm, one may use an extra buffer for sub-pixel data.
[src:graphics/spatial-anti-aliasing] The initial (and least memory-hungry) approach used 16 extra bits per pixel, in a 4 × 4 grid.
[src:graphics/spatial-anti-aliasing] If one renders the primitives in a careful order, such as front-to-back, it is possible to create a reasonable image.
[src:graphics/spatial-anti-aliasing] Since this requires that the primitives be in some order, and hence interacts poorly with an application programming interface such as OpenGL, the latest methods simply have two or more full sub-pixels per pixel, including full color information for each sub-pixel.
[src:graphics/spatial-anti-aliasing] There is also an approach specialised for texture mapping called mipmapping, which works by creating lower resolution, pre-filtered versions of the texture map.
[src:graphics/spatial-anti-aliasing] When rendering the image, the appropriate-resolution mipmap is chosen and hence the texture pixels (texels) are already filtered when they arrive on the screen.
[src:graphics/spatial-anti-aliasing] Mipmapping is generally combined with various forms of texture filtering in order to improve the final result.
[src:graphics/spatial-anti-aliasing] Because fractals have unlimited detail and no noise other than arithmetic round-off error, they illustrate aliasing more clearly than do photographs or other measured data.
[src:graphics/spatial-anti-aliasing] The escape times, which are converted to colours at the exact centres of the pixels, go to infinity at the border of the set, so colours from centres near borders are unpredictable, due to aliasing.
[src:graphics/spatial-anti-aliasing] This example has edges in about half of its pixels, so it shows much aliasing.
[src:graphics/spatial-anti-aliasing] The first image is uploaded at its original sampling rate.
[src:graphics/spatial-anti-aliasing] (Since most modern software anti-aliases, one may have to download the full-size version to see all of the aliasing.) The second image is calculated at five times the sampling rate and down-sampled with anti-aliasing.
[src:graphics/spatial-anti-aliasing] Assuming that one would really like something like the average colour over each pixel, this one is getting closer.
[src:graphics/spatial-anti-aliasing] It is clearly more orderly than the first.
[src:graphics/spatial-anti-aliasing] In order to properly compare these images, viewing them at full-scale is necessary.
[src:graphics/spatial-anti-aliasing] It happens that, in this case, there is additional information that can be used.
[src:graphics/spatial-anti-aliasing] By re-calculating with a "distance estimator" algorithm, points were identified that are very close to the edge of the set, so that unusually fine detail is aliased in from the rapidly changing escape times near the edge of the set.
[src:graphics/spatial-anti-aliasing] The colours derived from these calculated points have been identified as unusually unrepresentative of their pixels.
[src:graphics/spatial-anti-aliasing] The set changes more rapidly there, so a single point sample is less representative of the whole pixel.
[src:graphics/spatial-anti-aliasing] Those points were replaced, in the third image, by interpolating the points around them.
[src:graphics/spatial-anti-aliasing] This reduces the noisiness of the image but has the side effect of brightening the colours.
[src:graphics/spatial-anti-aliasing] So this image is not exactly the same that would be obtained with an even larger set of calculated points.
[src:graphics/spatial-anti-aliasing] To show what was discarded, the rejected points, blended into a grey background, are shown in the fourth image.
[src:graphics/spatial-anti-aliasing] Finally, "Budding Turbines" is so regular that systematic (Moiré) aliasing can clearly be seen near the main "turbine axis" when it is downsized by taking the nearest pixel.
[src:graphics/spatial-anti-aliasing] The aliasing in the first image appears random because it comes from all levels of detail, below the pixel size.
[src:graphics/spatial-anti-aliasing] When the lower level aliasing is suppressed, to make the third image and then that is down-sampled once more, without anti-aliasing, to make the fifth image, the order on the scale of the third image appears as systematic aliasing in the fifth image.
[src:graphics/spatial-anti-aliasing] Super sampling anti-aliasing (SSAA), also called full-scene anti-aliasing (FSAA), is used to avoid aliasing (or "jaggies") on full-screen images.
[src:graphics/spatial-anti-aliasing] SSAA was the first type of anti-aliasing available with early video cards.
[src:graphics/spatial-anti-aliasing] But due to its tremendous computational cost and the advent of multisample anti-aliasing (MSAA) support on GPUs, it is no longer widely used in real time applications.
[src:graphics/spatial-anti-aliasing] MSAA provides somewhat lower graphic quality, but also tremendous savings in computational power.
[src:graphics/spatial-anti-aliasing] The resulting image of SSAA may seem softer, and should also appear more realistic.
[src:graphics/spatial-anti-aliasing] However, while useful for photo-like images, a simple anti-aliasing approach (such as super-sampling and then averaging) may actually worsen the appearance of some types of line art or diagrams (making the image appear fuzzy), especially where most lines are horizontal or vertical.
[src:graphics/spatial-anti-aliasing] In these cases, a prior grid-fitting step may be useful (see hinting).
[src:graphics/spatial-anti-aliasing] In general, super-sampling is a technique of collecting data points at a greater resolution (usually by a power of two) than the final data resolution.
[src:graphics/spatial-anti-aliasing] These data points are then combined (down-sampled) to the desired resolution, often just by a simple average.
[src:graphics/spatial-anti-aliasing] The combined data points have less visible aliasing artifacts (or moiré patterns).
[src:graphics/spatial-anti-aliasing] Full-scene anti-aliasing by super-sampling usually means that each full frame is rendered at double (2x) or quadruple (4x) the display resolution, and then down-sampled to match the display resolution.
[src:graphics/spatial-anti-aliasing] Thus, a 2x FSAA would render 4 super-sampled pixels for each single pixel of each frame.
[src:graphics/spatial-anti-aliasing] Rendering at larger resolutions will produce better results; however, more processor power is needed, which can degrade performance and frame rate.
[src:graphics/spatial-anti-aliasing] Sometimes FSAA is implemented in hardware in such a way that a graphical application is unaware the images are being super-sampled and then down-sampled before being displayed.
[src:graphics/spatial-anti-aliasing] A graphics rendering system creates an image based on objects constructed of polygonal primitives; the aliasing effects in the image can be reduced by applying an anti-aliasing scheme only to the areas of the image representing silhouette edges of the objects.
[src:graphics/spatial-anti-aliasing] The silhouette edges are anti-aliased by creating anti-aliasing primitives which vary in opacity.
[src:graphics/spatial-anti-aliasing] These anti-aliasing primitives are joined to the silhouetted edges, and create a region in the image where the objects appear to blend into the background.
[src:graphics/spatial-anti-aliasing] The method has some important advantages over classical methods based on the accumulation buffer since it generates full-scene anti-aliasing in only two passes and does not require the use of additional memory required by the accumulation buffer.
[src:graphics/spatial-anti-aliasing] Object-based anti-aliasing was first developed at Silicon Graphics for their Indy workstation.
[src:graphics/spatial-anti-aliasing] Digital images are usually stored in a gamma-compressed format, but most optical anti-aliasing filters are linear.
[src:graphics/spatial-anti-aliasing] So to down-sample an image in a way that would match optical blurring, one should first convert it to a linear format, then apply the anti-aliasing filter, and finally convert it back to a gamma compressed format.
[src:graphics/spatial-anti-aliasing] Using linear arithmetic on a gamma-compressed image results in values which are slightly different from the ideal filter.
[src:graphics/spatial-anti-aliasing] This error is larger when dealing with high contrast areas, causing high contrast areas to become dimmer: bright details (such as a cat's whiskers) become visually thinner, and dark details (such as tree branches) become thicker, relative to the optically anti-aliased image.
[src:graphics/spatial-anti-aliasing] Each pixel is individually distorted, meaning outlines become unsmooth after anti-aliasing.
[src:graphics/spatial-anti-aliasing] Because the conversion to and from a linear format greatly slows down the process, and because the differences are usually subtle, most image editing software, including Final Cut Pro and Adobe Photoshop, process images in the gamma-compressed domain.
[src:graphics/spatial-anti-aliasing] Most modern GPUs support storing textures in memory in sRGB format, and can perform transformation to linear space and back transparently, with essentially no loss in performance.
[src:graphics/texture-mapping] A *texture map* refers to a 2D image ("texture") that adds visual detail to a 3D model.
[src:graphics/texture-mapping] The image can be stored as a raster graphic.
[src:graphics/texture-mapping] The coordinate space that converts from a 3D model's 3D space into a 2D space for sampling from the texture map is variously called *UV space*, *UV coordinates*, or *texture space*.
[src:graphics/texture-mapping] The UV Coordinates are used to read the color from the texture and apply it to the pixel.
[src:graphics/texture-mapping] The original technique was pioneered by Edwin Catmull in 1974 as part of his doctoral thesis.
[src:graphics/texture-mapping] Texture mapping originally referred to *diffuse mapping*, a method that simply mapped pixels from a texture to a 3D surface ("wrapping" the image around the object).
[src:graphics/texture-mapping] A **texture map** is an image applied ("mapped") to the surface of a shape or polygon.
[src:graphics/texture-mapping] This may be a bitmap image or a procedural texture.
[src:graphics/texture-mapping] They may be stored in common image file formats, referenced by 3D model formats or material definitions, and assembled into resource bundles.
[src:graphics/texture-mapping] They may have one to three dimensions, although two dimensions are most common for visible surfaces.
[src:graphics/texture-mapping] For use with modern hardware, texture map data may be stored in swizzled or tiled orderings to improve cache coherency.
[src:graphics/texture-mapping] Rendering APIs typically manage texture map resources (which may be located in device memory) as buffers or surfaces, and may allow 'render to texture' for additional effects such as post processing or environment mapping.
[src:graphics/texture-mapping] Texture maps usually contain RGB color data (either stored as direct color, compressed formats, or indexed color), and sometimes an additional channel for alpha blending (RGBA) especially for billboards and decal overlay textures.
[src:graphics/texture-mapping] It is possible to use the alpha channel (which may be convenient to store in formats parsed by hardware) for other uses such as specularity.
[src:graphics/texture-mapping] Multiple texture maps (or channels) may be combined for control over specularity, normals, displacement, or subsurface scattering, e.g. for skin rendering.
[src:graphics/texture-mapping] Multiple texture images may be combined in texture atlases or array textures to reduce state changes for modern hardware.
[src:graphics/texture-mapping] (They may be considered a modern evolution of tile map graphics).
[src:graphics/texture-mapping] Modern hardware often supports cube map textures with multiple faces for environment mapping.
[src:graphics/texture-mapping] Texture maps may be acquired by scanning or digital photography, designed in image manipulation software such as GIMP or Photoshop, or painted onto 3D surfaces directly in a 3D paint tool such as Mudbox or ZBrush.
[src:graphics/texture-mapping] Every vertex in a polygon is assigned a texture coordinate (which in the 2D case is also known as UV coordinates).
[src:graphics/texture-mapping] This may be done through explicit assignment of vertex attributes, manually edited in a 3D modelling package through UV unwrapping tools.
[src:graphics/texture-mapping] It is also possible to associate a procedural transformation from 3D space to texture space with the material.
[src:graphics/texture-mapping] This might be accomplished via planar projection or, alternatively, cylindrical or spherical mapping.
[src:graphics/texture-mapping] More complex mappings may consider the distance along a surface to minimize distortion.
[src:graphics/texture-mapping] These coordinates are interpolated across the faces of polygons to sample the texture map during rendering.
[src:graphics/texture-mapping] Textures may be repeated or mirrored to extend a finite rectangular bitmap over a larger area, or they may have a one-to-one unique "injective" mapping from every piece of a surface (which is important for render mapping and light mapping, also known as baking).
[src:graphics/texture-mapping] Texture mapping maps the model surface (or screen space during rasterization) into *texture space*; in this space, the texture map is visible in its undistorted form.
[src:graphics/texture-mapping] UV unwrapping tools typically provide a view in texture space for manual editing of texture coordinates.
[src:graphics/texture-mapping] Some rendering techniques such as subsurface scattering may be performed approximately by texture-space operations.
[src:graphics/texture-mapping] For instance, a light map texture may be used to light a surface as an alternative to recalculating that lighting every time the surface is rendered.
[src:graphics/texture-mapping] *Microtextures* or *detail textures* are used to add higher frequency details, and *dirt maps* add weathering and variation; this can greatly reduce the apparent periodicity of repeating textures.
[src:graphics/texture-mapping] Modern graphics may use more than 10 layers, which are combined using shaders, for greater fidelity.
[src:graphics/texture-mapping] Bump mapping has become popular in video games, as graphics hardware has become powerful enough to accommodate it in real-time.
[src:graphics/texture-mapping] The way that samples (e.g. when viewed as pixels on the screen) are calculated from the texels (texture pixels) is governed by texture filtering.
[src:graphics/texture-mapping] The cheapest method is to use the nearest-neighbour interpolation, but bilinear interpolation or trilinear interpolation between mipmaps are two commonly used alternatives which reduce aliasing or jaggies.
[src:graphics/texture-mapping] In the event of a texture coordinate being outside the texture, it is either clamped or wrapped.
[src:graphics/texture-mapping] Anisotropic filtering better eliminates directional artefacts when viewing textures from oblique viewing angles.
[src:graphics/texture-mapping] Texture streaming is a means of using data streams for textures, where each texture is available in two or more different resolutions, as to determine which texture should be loaded into memory and used based on draw distance from the viewer and how much memory is available for textures.
[src:graphics/texture-mapping] Texture streaming allows a rendering engine to use low resolution textures for objects far away from the viewer's camera, and resolve those into more detailed textures, read from a data source, as the point of view nears the objects.
[src:graphics/texture-mapping] As an optimization, it is possible to render detail from a complex, high-resolution model or expensive process (such as global illumination) into a surface texture (possibly on a low-resolution model).
[src:graphics/texture-mapping] This technique is called *baking* (or *render mapping*) and is most commonly used for light maps, but may also be used to generate normal maps and displacement maps.
[src:graphics/texture-mapping] The original *Quake* software engine used on-the-fly baking to combine light maps and colour maps in a process called *surface caching*.
[src:graphics/texture-mapping] Baking can be used as a form of level of detail generation, where a complex scene with many different elements and materials may be approximated by a single element with a single texture, which is then algorithmically reduced for lower rendering cost and fewer drawcalls.
[src:graphics/texture-mapping] It is also used to take high-detail models from 3D sculpting software and point cloud scanning and approximate them with meshes more suitable for realtime rendering.
[src:graphics/texture-mapping] Various techniques have evolved in software and hardware implementations.
[src:graphics/texture-mapping] Each offers different trade-offs in precision, versatility, and performance.
[src:graphics/texture-mapping] In contrast to perpendicular polygons, this leads to noticeable distortion with perspective transformations (as shown in the figure: the checker box texture appears bent), especially as primitives near the camera.
[src:graphics/texture-mapping] This distortion can be reduced by subdividing polygons into smaller polygons.
[src:graphics/texture-mapping] Using quad primitives for rectangular objects can look less incorrect than if those rectangles were split into triangles.
[src:graphics/texture-mapping] However, since interpolating four points adds complexity to the rasterization, most early implementations preferred triangles only.
[src:graphics/texture-mapping] Some hardware, such as the forward texture mapping used by the Nvidia NV1, offered efficient quad primitives.
[src:graphics/texture-mapping] With perspective correction, triangles become equivalent to quad primitives and this advantage disappears.
[src:graphics/texture-mapping] For rectangular objects that are at right angles to the viewer (like floors and walls), the perspective only needs to be corrected in one direction across the screen rather than both.
[src:graphics/texture-mapping] The correct perspective mapping can be calculated at the left and right edges of the floor.
[src:graphics/texture-mapping] Affine linear interpolation across that horizontal span will look correct because every pixel along that line is the same distance from the viewer.
[src:graphics/texture-mapping] In contrast, the original z , u , and v , before the division, are not linear across the surface in screen space.
[src:graphics/texture-mapping] It is therefore possible to linearly interpolate these reciprocals across the surface, computing corrected values at each pixel, to produce a perspective correct texture mapping.
[src:graphics/texture-mapping] To do this, the reciprocals at each vertex of the geometry (three points for a triangle) are calculated.
[src:graphics/texture-mapping] Then, linear interpolation can be done on these reciprocals between the n vertices (e.g., using barycentric coordinates), resulting in interpolated values across the surface.
[src:graphics/texture-mapping] However, as our division by z altered their coordinate system, this $u_{i},v_{i}$ cannot be used as texture coordinates.
[src:graphics/texture-mapping] To correct back to the $u,v$ space, the corrected z is calculated by taking the reciprocal once again: $z_{correct}={\frac {1}{\frac {1}{z_{i}}}}$ .
[src:graphics/texture-mapping] This correction makes it so that the difference from pixel to pixel between texture coordinates is smaller in parts of the polygon that are closer to the viewer (stretching the texture wider) and is larger in parts that are farther away (compressing the texture).
[src:graphics/texture-mapping] Affine texture mapping directly interpolates a texture coordinate $u_{\alpha }$ between two endpoints $u_{0}$ and $u_{1}$ : $u_{\alpha }=(1-\alpha )u_{0}+\alpha u_{1}$ where $0\leq \alpha \leq 1$ .
[src:graphics/texture-mapping] Various techniques have evolved for rendering texture mapped geometry into images with different quality and precision trade-offs, which can be applied to both software and hardware.
[src:graphics/texture-mapping] Classic software texture mappers generally only performed simple texture mapping with one lighting effect at most (typically applied through a lookup table), and the perspective correctness was about 16 times more expensive.
[src:graphics/texture-mapping] The *Doom* engine restricted the world to vertical walls and horizontal floors and ceilings, with a camera that could only rotate about the vertical axis.
[src:graphics/texture-mapping] This meant the walls would be a constant depth coordinate along a vertical line and the floors and ceilings would have a constant depth along a horizontal line.
[src:graphics/texture-mapping] After performing one perspective correction calculation for the depth, the rest of the line could use fast affine mapping.
[src:graphics/texture-mapping] Some later renderers of this era simulated a small amount of camera pitch with shearing which allowed the appearance of greater freedom while using the same rendering technique.
[src:graphics/texture-mapping] Some engines were able to render texture mapped heightmaps (e.g.
[src:graphics/texture-mapping] Nova Logic's Voxel Space, and the engine for *Outcast*) via Bresenham-like incremental algorithms, producing the appearance of a texture mapped landscape without the use of traditional geometric primitives.
[src:graphics/texture-mapping] Every triangle can be further subdivided into groups of about 16 pixels in order to achieve two goals: keeping the arithmetic mill busy at all times and producing faster arithmetic results.
[src:graphics/texture-mapping] For perspective texture mapping without hardware support, a triangle is broken down into smaller triangles for rendering and affine mapping is used on them.
[src:graphics/texture-mapping] The reason this technique works is that the distortion of affine mapping becomes much less noticeable on smaller polygons.
[src:graphics/texture-mapping] The Sony PlayStation made extensive use of this because it only supported affine mapping in hardware and had a relatively high triangle throughput compared to its peers.
[src:graphics/texture-mapping] Software renderers generally prefer screen subdivision because it has less overhead.
[src:graphics/texture-mapping] Additionally, they try to do linear interpolation along a line of pixels to simplify the set-up (compared to 2D affine interpolation), thus lessening the overhead further.
[src:graphics/texture-mapping] Another reason is that affine texture mapping does not fit into the low number of CPU registers of the x86 CPU; the 68000 and RISC processors are much more suited for that approach.
[src:graphics/texture-mapping] As the polygons are rendered independently, it may be possible to switch between spans and columns or diagonal directions depending on the orientation of the polygon normal to achieve a more constant z, but the effort seems not to be worth it.
[src:graphics/texture-mapping] One other technique is to approximate the perspective with a faster calculation, such as a polynomial.
[src:graphics/texture-mapping] A second uses the ${\textstyle {\frac {1}{z_{i}}}}$ value of the last two drawn pixels to linearly extrapolate the next value.
[src:graphics/texture-mapping] For the latter, the division is then done starting from those values so that all that has to be divided is a small remainder.
[src:graphics/texture-mapping] However, the amount of bookkeeping needed makes this technique too slow on most systems.
[src:graphics/texture-mapping] A third technique, used by the Build Engine (used, most notably, in *Duke Nukem 3D*), builds on the constant distance trick used by the *Doom* engine by finding and rendering along the line of constant distance for arbitrary polygons.
[src:graphics/texture-mapping] Texture mapping hardware was originally developed for simulation (e.g. as implemented in the Evans and Sutherland ESIG and Singer-Link Digital Image Generators DIG) and professional graphics workstations (such as Silicon Graphics) and broadcast digital video effects machines such as the Ampex ADO.
[src:graphics/texture-mapping] Texture mapping hardware later appeared in arcade cabinets, consumer video game consoles, and PC video cards in the mid-1990s.
[src:graphics/texture-mapping] In flight simulations, texture mapping provided important motion and altitude cues necessary for pilot training not available on untextured surfaces.
[src:graphics/texture-mapping] Additionally, texture mapping was implemented so that real-time processing of prefiltered texture patterns stored in memory could be accessed by the video processor in real-time.
[src:graphics/texture-mapping] Modern graphics processing units (GPUs) provide specialised fixed function units called *texture samplers*, or *texture mapping units*, to perform texture mapping, usually with trilinear filtering or better multi-tap anisotropic filtering and hardware for decoding specific formats such as DXTn.
[src:graphics/texture-mapping] As of 2016, texture mapping hardware is ubiquitous as most SOCs contain a suitable GPU.
[src:graphics/texture-mapping] Some hardware implementations combine texture mapping with hidden-surface determination in tile-based deferred rendering or scanline rendering; such systems only fetch the visible texels at the expense of using greater workspace for transformed vertices.
[src:graphics/texture-mapping] Most systems have settled on the z-buffering approach, which can still reduce the texture mapping workload with front-to-back sorting.
[src:graphics/texture-mapping] Inverse texture mapping instead iterates through pixels on the screen and decides what texel to use for each.
[src:graphics/texture-mapping] Of these methods, inverse texture mapping has become standard in modern hardware.
[src:graphics/texture-mapping] With this method, a pixel on the screen is mapped to a point on the texture.
[src:graphics/texture-mapping] Each vertex of a rendering primitive is projected to a point on the screen, and each of these points is mapped to a u,v texel coordinate on the texture.
[src:graphics/texture-mapping] A rasterizer will interpolate between these points to fill in each pixel covered by the primitive.
[src:graphics/texture-mapping] The primary advantage of this method is that each pixel covered by a primitive will be traversed exactly once.
[src:graphics/texture-mapping] Once a primitive's vertices are transformed, the amount of remaining work scales directly with how many pixels it covers on the screen.
[src:graphics/texture-mapping] The main disadvantage is that the memory access pattern in the texture space will not be linear if the texture is at an angle to the screen.
[src:graphics/texture-mapping] This disadvantage is often addressed by texture caching techniques, such as the swizzled texture memory arrangement.
[src:graphics/texture-mapping] The linear interpolation can be used directly for simple and efficient affine texture mapping, but can also be adapted for perspective correctness.
[src:graphics/texture-mapping] Forward texture mapping maps each texel of the texture to a pixel on the screen.
[src:graphics/texture-mapping] After transforming a rectangular primitive to a place on the screen, a forward texture mapping renderer iterates through each texel on the texture, splatting each one onto a pixel of the frame buffer.
[src:graphics/texture-mapping] This was used by some hardware, such as the 3DO, the Sega Saturn and the NV1.
[src:graphics/texture-mapping] The primary advantage is that the texture will be accessed in a simple linear order, allowing very efficient caching of the texture data.
[src:graphics/texture-mapping] However, this benefit is also its disadvantage: as a primitive gets smaller on screen, it still has to iterate over every texel in the texture, causing many pixels to be overdrawn redundantly.
[src:graphics/texture-mapping] This method is also well suited for rendering quad primitives rather than reducing them to triangles, which provided an advantage when perspective correct texturing was not available in hardware.
[src:graphics/texture-mapping] This is because the affine distortion of a quad looks less incorrect than the same quad split into two triangles .
[src:graphics/texture-mapping] The NV1 hardware also allowed a quadratic interpolation mode to provide an even better approximation of perspective correctness.
[src:graphics/texture-mapping] UV mapping became an important technique for 3D modelling and assisted in clipping the texture correctly when the primitive went past the edge of the screen, but existing hardware did not provide effective implementations of this.
[src:graphics/texture-mapping] These shortcomings could have been addressed with further development, but GPU design has mostly shifted toward using the inverse mapping technique.
[src:graphics/texture-mapping] It is possible to use texture mapping hardware to accelerate both the reconstruction of voxel data sets from tomographic scans, and to visualize the results.
[src:graphics/texture-mapping] Many user interfaces use texture mapping to accelerate animated transitions of screen elements, e.g.
[src:graphics/z-buffering] A **z-buffer**, also known as a **depth buffer**, is a type of data buffer used in computer graphics to store the depth information of fragments.
[src:graphics/z-buffering] The values stored represent the distance to the camera, with 0 being the closest.
[src:graphics/z-buffering] The encoding scheme may be flipped with the highest number being the value closest to camera.
[src:graphics/z-buffering] In a 3D-rendering pipeline, when an object is projected on the screen, the depth (z-value) of a generated fragment in the projected screen image is compared to the value already stored in the buffer (**depth test**), and replaces it if the new value is closer.
[src:graphics/z-buffering] It works in tandem with the rasterizer, which computes the colored values.
[src:graphics/z-buffering] The fragment output by the rasterizer is saved if it is not overlapped by another fragment.
[src:graphics/z-buffering] Z-buffering is a technique used in almost all contemporary computers, laptops, and mobile phones for generating 3D computer graphics.
[src:graphics/z-buffering] The primary use now is for video games, which require fast and accurate processing of 3D scenes.
[src:graphics/z-buffering] Determining what should be displayed on the screen and what should be omitted is a multi-step process utilising various techniques.
[src:graphics/z-buffering] Using a z-buffer is the final step in this process.
[src:graphics/z-buffering] If the z-value is further away than the value in the z-buffer, the fragment is discarded.
[src:graphics/z-buffering] This is repeated for all objects and surfaces in the scene (often in parallel).
[src:graphics/z-buffering] In the end, the z-buffer will allow correct reproduction of the usual depth perception: a close object hides one further away.
[src:graphics/z-buffering] The granularity of a z-buffer has a great influence on the scene quality: the traditional 16-bit z-buffer can result in artifacts (called "z-fighting" or **stitching**) when two objects are very close to each other.
[src:graphics/z-buffering] A more modern 24-bit or 32-bit z-buffer behaves much better, although the problem cannot be eliminated without additional algorithms.
[src:graphics/z-buffering] An 8-bit z-buffer is almost never used since it has too little precision.
[src:graphics/z-buffering] Z-buffer data obtained from rendering a surface from a light's point-of-view permits the creation of shadows by the shadow mapping technique.
[src:graphics/z-buffering] Z-buffering was first described in 1974 by Wolfgang Straßer in his PhD thesis on fast algorithms for rendering occluded objects.
[src:graphics/z-buffering] A similar solution to determining overlapping polygons is the painter's algorithm, which is capable of handling non-opaque scene elements, though at the cost of efficiency and incorrect results.
[src:graphics/z-buffering] Z-buffers are often implemented in hardware within consumer graphics cards.
[src:graphics/z-buffering] Z-buffering is also used (implemented as software as opposed to hardware) for producing computer-generated special effects for films.
[src:graphics/z-buffering] Even with small enough granularity, quality problems may arise when precision in the z-buffer's distance values are not spread evenly over distance.
[src:graphics/z-buffering] Nearer values are much more precise (and hence can display closer objects better) than values that are farther away.
[src:graphics/z-buffering] Generally, this is desirable, but sometimes it will cause artifacts to appear as objects become more distant.
[src:graphics/z-buffering] A variation on z-buffering which results in more evenly distributed precision is called **w-buffering** (see below).
[src:graphics/z-buffering] At the start of a new scene, the z-buffer must be cleared to a defined value, usually 1.0, because this value is the upper limit (on a scale of 0 to 1) of depth, meaning that no object is present at this point through the viewing frustum.
[src:graphics/z-buffering] The invention of the z-buffer concept is most often attributed to Edwin Catmull, although Wolfgang Straßer described this idea in his 1974 Ph.D. thesis months before Catmull's invention.
[src:graphics/z-buffering] On more recent PC graphics cards (1999–2005), z-buffer management uses a significant chunk of the available memory bandwidth.
[src:graphics/z-buffering] Super Smash Bros. and F-Zero X are two Nintendo 64 games that minimized z-buffering to increase framerates.
[src:graphics/z-buffering] Several Factor 5 games also minimized or omitted z-buffering.
[src:graphics/z-buffering] On the Nintendo 64 z-Buffering can consume up to 4x as much bandwidth as opposed to not using z-buffering.
[src:graphics/z-buffering] Mechwarrior 2 on PC supported resolutions up to 800 × 600 on the original 4 MB 3dfx Voodoo due to not using z-buffering.
[src:graphics/z-buffering] In rendering, z-culling is early pixel elimination based on depth, a method that provides an increase in performance when rendering of hidden surfaces is costly.
[src:graphics/z-buffering] It is a direct consequence of z-buffering, where the depth of each pixel candidate is compared to the depth of the existing geometry behind which it might be hidden.
[src:graphics/z-buffering] When using a z-buffer, a pixel can be culled (discarded) as soon as its depth is known, which makes it possible to skip the entire process of lighting and texturing a pixel that would not be visible anyway.
[src:graphics/z-buffering] Also, time-consuming pixel shaders will generally not be executed for the culled pixels.
[src:graphics/z-buffering] This makes z-culling a good optimization candidate in situations where fillrate, lighting, texturing, or pixel shaders are the main bottlenecks.
[src:graphics/z-buffering] While z-buffering allows the geometry to be unsorted, sorting polygons by increasing depth (thus using a reverse painter's algorithm) allows each screen pixel to be rendered fewer times.
[src:graphics/z-buffering] As such, a reverse painter's algorithm cannot be used as an alternative to z-culling (without strenuous re-engineering), except as an optimization to z-culling.
[src:graphics/z-buffering] For example, an optimization might be to keep polygons sorted according to x/y-location and z-depth to provide bounds, in an effort to quickly determine if two polygons might possibly have an occlusion interaction.
[src:graphics/z-buffering] The range of depth values in camera space to be rendered is often defined between a ${\textit {near}}$ and ${\textit {far}}$ value of z .
[src:graphics/z-buffering] where z is the old value of z in camera space, and is sometimes called w or $w'$ .
[src:graphics/z-buffering] The resulting values of $z'$ are normalized between the values of –1 and 1, where the ${\textit {near}}$ plane is at –1 and the ${\mathit {far}}$ plane is at 1.
[src:graphics/z-buffering] Values outside of this range correspond to points which are not in the viewing frustum, and shouldn't be rendered.
[src:graphics/z-buffering] Typically, these values are stored in the z-buffer of the hardware graphics accelerator in fixed point format.
[src:graphics/z-buffering] This formula can be inverted and derived in order to calculate the z-buffer resolution (the "granularity" mentioned earlier).
[src:graphics/z-buffering] The z-buffer resolution in terms of camera space would be the incremental value resulted from the smallest change in the integer stored in the z-buffer, which is +1 or –1.
[src:graphics/z-buffering] This shows that the values of $z'$ are grouped much more densely near the ${\textit {near}}$ plane, and much more sparsely farther away, resulting in better precision closer to the camera.
[src:graphics/z-buffering] The smaller $near$ is, the less precision there is far away—having the $near$ plane set too closely is a common cause of undesirable rendering artifacts in more distant objects.
[src:graphics/z-buffering] To implement a z-buffer, the values of $z'$ are linearly interpolated across screen space between the vertices of the current polygon, and these intermediate values are generally stored in the z-buffer in fixed point format.
[src:graphics/z-buffering] To implement a w-buffer, the old values of z in camera space, or w , are stored in the buffer, generally in floating point format.
[src:graphics/z-buffering] However, these values cannot be linearly interpolated across screen space from the vertices—they usually have to be inverted, interpolated, and then inverted again.
[src:graphics/z-buffering] The resulting values of w , as opposed to $z'$ , are spaced evenly between ${\textit {near}}$ and ${\textit {far}}$ .
[src:graphics/z-buffering] There are implementations of the w-buffer that avoid the inversions altogether.
[src:graphics/z-buffering] Whether a z-buffer or w-buffer results in a better image depends on the application.
